const a = [
  {"id":2782,"text":"A 37-year-old woman with GERD and chronic hepatitis C genotype 1a infection is preparing to begin treatment with ledipasvir/sofosbuvir. Which is the most appropriate information for the patient regarding the use of a proton-pump inhibitor during treatment with ledipasvir/sofosbuvir?","explanation":"When a patient is on ledipasvir/sofosbuvir treatment for chronic hepatitis C, concurrent use of proton-pump inhibitors (PPIs) can be problematic. Ledipasvir, a component of this combination therapy, requires an acidic environment in the stomach for optimal absorption. PPIs, by their mechanism of action, suppress stomach acid production and increase gastric pH. An elevated pH in the stomach can lead to reduced absorption of ledipasvir. Therefore, to ensure effective hepatitis C treatment, the patient should ideally stop using the proton-pump inhibitor while on ledipasvir/sofosbuvir.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 453.","responses":[{"text":"Absorption of ledipasvir is increased with increasing pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorption of ledipasvir is not affected by gastric pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A proton-pump inhibitor can be safely administered with ledipasvir/sofosbuvir without regard to timing of the dose or food intake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorption of sofosbuvir is decreased with increasing pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The patient should stop using the proton-pump inhibitor","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4628,"text":"A 60-year-old man is called for a follow-up 2 weeks after his surgery for colon cancer. During the surgery, his tumor was removed and a permanent stoma was made. What is the most likely procedure performed?","explanation":"In this patient who underwent surgery for colon cancer and had a tumor removed with the creation of a permanent stoma, the most likely procedure performed is an **abdominoperineal resection**. This procedure involves the removal of the lower part of the rectum and anus, thereby necessitating the creation of a permanent colostomy, or stoma, for the passage of feces.\r\n\r\n\r\n**Peustow's procedure** is done to drain the main pancreatic duct in cases of chronic pancreatitis with large ductal dilatation.\r\n  \r\n**Billroth I procedure** is a type of gastrectomy, specifically a partial gastrectomy, where the remaining stomach is anastomosed directly to the duodenum.\r\n\r\n**Whipple's procedure** or pancreaticoduodenectomy is a complex surgical procedure used primarily to treat cancerous tumors of the head of the pancreas. It involves removal of the pancreatic head, duodenum, and a portion of the bile duct.\r\n\r\n**Low anterior resection** is a surgery used to treat rectal cancers. Here, the tumor is removed, and the remaining parts of the rectum and colon are joined together, avoiding the need for a permanent stoma in most cases.","reference":"Wei R, Crook C, Bamford R. Abdominoperineal resection. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed August 30, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574568/","responses":[{"text":"Whipple's procedure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low anterior resection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Billroth I procedure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peustow's procedure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominoperineal resection","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4644,"text":"A 15-year-old boy presents to the clinic with increased bloating, abdominal pain, and explosive diarrhea upon ingestion of dairy products for the past several months. What is the most likely etiology for this condition?","explanation":"This patient presenting with bloating, abdominal pain, and explosive diarrhea upon ingestion of dairy products most likely has **disaccharidase deficiency**. This specifically refers to lactase deficiency, which results in the inability to digest lactose, a sugar found in dairy products. Undigested lactose in the intestines can lead to bacterial fermentation, producing the symptoms described.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nIrritable bowel syndrome (IBS) is a functional gastrointestinal disorder characterized by chronic abdominal pain and altered bowel habits without any organic cause. Symptoms are not specifically triggered by dairy.\r\n\r\nVillous blunting is a feature of celiac disease. People with this condition have an immune response to gluten, leading to inflammation and damage to the lining of the small intestine. While it can cause similar gastrointestinal symptoms, it is triggered by gluten ingestion, not dairy.\r\n\r\nTropical sprue is a malabsorptive disorder seen in residents or long-term visitors of tropical regions. It leads to malabsorption and can cause diarrhea, but it's not specifically related to dairy intake.\r\n\r\nGiardiasis is an intestinal infection caused by the protozoan parasite *Giardia lamblia*. It can lead to symptoms of diarrhea, gas, and stomach cramps, but the presentation is not specific to dairy consumption.","reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 812.\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 785.","responses":[{"text":"Tropical sprue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disaccharidase deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous blunting","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4655,"text":"What is the investigation of choice to determine patency of the distal portion of intestine prior to a defunctioning stoma reversal surgery?","explanation":"**Loopogram** is the investigation of choice to determine the patency of the distal portion of the intestine prior to a defunctioning stoma reversal surgery. A water-soluble contrast is instilled through the stoma into the bowel to assess its patency, integrity, and to check for any leakage or stricture before considering reversal of the stoma.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Colonoscopy** can visualize the interior lining of the colon and rectum but is not the first choice for checking patency in the context of stoma reversal. It's more invasive and may not be necessary if the loopogram is clear.\r\n\r\n**Barium follow-through** is an imaging procedure where a patient swallows barium, a contrast material, and X-rays are taken as the barium moves through the small intestine. It's more commonly used for small bowel evaluation.\r\n\r\n**Contrast-enhanced computed tomography** is not the primary modality to assess distal bowel patency in the context of stoma reversal.\r\n\r\n**Sigmoidoscopy** is a procedure that allows visualization of the sigmoid colon. It might be used in certain situations but is not the primary test to determine patency before stoma reversal.","reference":"Poh KS, Hoh SY, Aziz R, Chong SS, Roslani AC. Delayed bowel perforation after routine distal loopogram prior to ileostomy closure. Open Medicine (Warsaw, Poland). Published 2020. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32292822/","responses":[{"text":"Colonoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium follow-through","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loopogram","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Contrast-enhanced computed tomography (CECT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sigmoidoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5109,"text":"Intestinal chyme stimulates the gastric secretion of about 10% of the acid in response to the meal. This early intestinal phase of stomach secretion is stimulated by which of the following?","explanation":"The early intestinal phase of stomach secretion is stimulated by **gastrin**. When chyme enters the duodenum, the presence of amino acids and peptides, in particular, stimulates the G cells in the duodenum to release gastrin, which then promotes further gastric acid secretion in the stomach.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSecretin is released in response to the acidic chyme in the duodenum. Its main role is to stimulate the pancreas to release bicarbonate-rich pancreatic juice, which neutralizes the acidic chyme. It does not stimulate gastric acid secretion; in fact, it inhibits it.\r\n\r\nAmino acids can stimulate gastrin release, but the primary stimulant for the early intestinal phase is gastrin itself.\r\n\r\nThe presence of fats in the duodenum stimulates the release of cholecystokinin (CCK) and secretin, which are involved in fat digestion and neutralizing stomach acid, respectively. They don't promote gastric acid secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 814.","responses":[{"text":"Fat in duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reverse enterogastric reflex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amino acids in duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5411,"text":"A 48-year-old female patient is brought to the emergency department with complaints of severe epigastric pain for 1 day, which became generalized and more severe for 3 hours. The pain is associated with vomiting, and she cannot tolerate even a liquid diet. She has a history of NSAID use for osteoarthritis for a long time. Her pulse is 120 beats/min, her blood pressure (BP) is 100/60 mmHg, she is afebrile, and her respiratory rate is 32 breaths/min. She has a tense tender abdomen with board-like rigidity. Gut sounds are inaudible. What is the most likely diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this patient is **perforated peptic ulcer**. The clinical picture of the patient, including sudden severe pain, **history of NSAID use**, vomiting, inability to tolerate oral intake, and especially the physical examination findings of a rigid, \"board-like\" abdomen with absent gut sounds, suggests a **perforation of the gastrointestinal tract leading to peritonitis**. Peptic ulcers, especially in the setting of prolonged NSAID use, can perforate, leading to the leakage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Perforated gallbladder** typically presents with right upper quadrant pain and not generalized abdominal pain with board-like rigidity. \r\n\r\nWhile the patient does likely have an underlying peptic ulcer (given her history of NSAID use), the acute presentation with the rigidity of the abdomen is more consistent with a perforated peptic ulcer rather than just a peptic ulcer.\r\n\r\n**Acute cholecystitis** usually presents with right upper quadrant pain that may radiate to the right shoulder, often triggered by a fatty meal.\r\n\r\n**Acute pancreatitis** condition can cause severe epigastric pain radiating to the back and may be associated with nausea and vomiting. The abdomen is usually tender but not rigid like in perforation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 766, 767.","responses":[{"text":"Peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated peptic ulcer","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5657,"text":"A 30-year-old female developed bleeding after excessive bouts of vomiting. The bleeding stopped spontaneously. Upper GI endoscopy showed longitudinal mucosal lacerations in the lower part of the esophagus. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Mallory-Weiss tears** are characterized by **longitudinal mucosal lacerations** in the lower part of the esophagus and occasionally the upper part of the stomach, typically at the **gastroesophageal junction**. They are often associated with **bouts of severe vomiting** and can result in hematemesis (vomiting of blood). The condition is self-limiting in many cases, with bleeding stopping spontaneously.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile esophageal cancer can present with bleeding, it does not typically arise after episodes of vomiting. The primary symptoms are dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), unintentional weight loss, and often, a longer history of symptoms.\r\n\r\nEsophageal erosions refer to superficial breaks in the esophageal mucosa, usually seen in conditions like gastroesophageal reflux disease. They can cause pain or discomfort but are not typically associated with severe vomiting and hematemesis.\r\n\r\nGastric varices are dilated veins in the stomach that can bleed, but they aren't typically associated with episodes of vomiting. They are more common in the setting of portal hypertension, such as in cirrhosis.\r\n\r\nLike gastric varices, esophageal varices are dilated veins, this time in the esophagus. They can bleed, especially if ruptured, and are also associated with portal hypertension. However, the association with vomiting and the endoscopic findings differentiate Mallory-Weiss tears from esophageal varices.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 754.","responses":[{"text":"Gastric varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory Weiss tears","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal erosions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5662,"text":"A 13-year-old child with a history of type 1 diabetes mellitus presents with intermittent diarrhea, abdominal pain, and vomiting. On examination, he has short stature with anemia, angular stomatitis, and paresthesia. What is the likely clinical diagnosis?","explanation":"**Celiac disease**, also known as gluten-sensitive enteropathy, is an **autoimmune condition** where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. Clinical features can include chronic diarrhea, abdominal pain, vomiting, short stature due to malabsorption, anemia, and other signs of nutrient deficiencies like angular stomatitis. The coexistence of type-1 diabetes mellitus and celiac disease is also well-recognized, as both conditions have an autoimmune etiology. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)** can cause abdominal pain and altered bowel habits, but it would not explain the anemia, short stature, or other specific symptoms mentioned.\r\n\r\n**Diabetic neuropathy** results from long-term high blood sugar levels and primarily affects the nerves, causing symptoms like numbness and pain. However, it would not account for the gastrointestinal symptoms or the anemia and angular stomatitis described.\r\n\r\n**Hypopituitarism** refers to decreased secretion of one or more of the pituitary hormones, leading to various symptoms depending on the hormone(s) affected. While it could cause growth issues, it would not typically present with the gastrointestinal symptoms mentioned.\r\n\r\n**Chronic giardiasis** is a parasitic infection that can cause diarrhea and abdominal pain, but it would not typically lead to the full spectrum of symptoms like angular stomatitis or the strong association with type-1 diabetes mellitus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 783.","responses":[{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypopituitarism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5669,"text":"A 26-year-old man suffered a heavy blow on the chin in boxing after which there was the escape of blood and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the nose, and extravasation of blood in the orbit which manifested as a \"black eye\". Which type of fracture could have led to this?","explanation":"A **fracture through the anterior cranial fossa** can be associated with a blow to the chin or frontal region. The fracture typically extends through the ethmoid bone, and patients may present with a **\"raccoon eye\" or \"black eye\"** due to blood accumulation in the orbit. CSF rhinorrhea, or the leakage of CSF from the nose, can also occur due to damage to the cribriform plate.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGutter fracture is a linear skull fracture that runs parallel to the major suture lines.\r\n\r\nFracture through the middle cranial fossa could potentially result in CSF otorrhea (leakage of CSF from the ear) and may damage the facial or auditory nerves.\r\n\r\nFracture through the posterior cranial fossa can be associated with CSF otorrhea but wouldn't typically cause a \"black eye\" or CSF rhinorrhea.\r\n\r\nHinge fracture occurs in the posterior aspect of the skull and is commonly associated with falls.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 242.","responses":[{"text":"Fracture through the anterior cranial fossa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gutter fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the middle cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the posterior cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hinge fracture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5682,"text":"A 35-year-old male patient was diagnosed with a peptic ulcer for the past 6 months. He is currently on maintenance therapy with H2 (histamine) receptor blockers along with a mucosal protective agent. Recently he complains of loss of libido and physical examination revealed signs of gynecomastia. Gynecomastia is the most common side effect of which of the following drug?","explanation":"*Cimetidine** is an H2 (histamine) receptor blocker used for the treatment of peptic ulcer disease. One of its notable side effects is **gynecomastia**, particularly with long-term use. The drug has **anti-androgenic effects**, which can lead to a loss of libido and gynecomastia in male patients.\r\n\r\nRoxatidine is another H2 receptor blocker used for the treatment of peptic ulcers. Gynecomastia is not a commonly reported side effect of this drug.\r\n\r\nFamotidine is yet another H2 receptor blocker. Although it shares a similar mechanism of action with cimetidine, it does not have the anti-androgenic effects that cimetidine possesses. As a result, gynecomastia is not a typical side effect of famotidine.\r\n\r\nOmeprazole is a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) used for the treatment of peptic ulcers and gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). Its mechanism of action and side effect profile are different from H2 blockers. It does not commonly cause gynecomastia.\r\n\r\nAluminum hydroxide is an antacid used to neutralize stomach acid. It can cause constipation as a side effect but does not typically cause gynecomastia.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Famotidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Roxatidine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5692,"text":"A 28-year-old lady falls from a scooter and gets minor abrasions on the arm and forearm and bruising of the scalp. After reaching home, she has a quarrel with her husband, receives mild blows on the face, and later dies. Autopsy reveals 100 ml of blood beneath a fractured skull at the site of the bruise. What is the probable cause of death?","explanation":"**Epidural hematoma** typically results from a traumatic injury, often associated with a fracture of the temporal bone. This can lead to rupture of the **middle meningeal artery**, causing blood to accumulate between the dura mater and the inner table of the skull. The classic presentation may include a **brief loss of consciousness (lucid interval)** followed by a **rapid decline in neurological status**, which could result in death if not treated promptly.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSubarachnoid hemorrhage usually occurs due to the rupture of a cerebral aneurysm and would present with sudden, severe headache often described as the \"worst headache of my life.\"\r\n\r\nContusions refer to brain bruises and are more commonly seen in deceleration injuries. While contusions can be fatal, the presentation given does not fit the classic scenario of a contusion as the cause of death.\r\n\r\nSubdural hematoma results from the tearing of bridging veins between the dura and arachnoid. It typically presents with a more insidious onset and might not be the result of a mild blow or trauma.\r\n\r\nIntracerebral hemorrhage refers to bleeding within the brain parenchyma itself. It can be due to hypertension, vascular malformations, or other causes but does not align with the trauma and rapid decline in this patient.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 243.","responses":[{"text":"Subarachnoid hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidural hematoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracerebral hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdural hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5693,"text":"A 30-year-old girl ingested an unknown substance and died. A post-mortem was carried out to find the cause of death. The oral cavity showed a diffuse grayish-white escharotic appearance. Also, the gastrointestinal (GI) tract was inflamed but the cecum and large intestine showed intense inflammation along with gangrene. What do you think is the probable substance she ingested?","explanation":"**Mercury** poisoning can result in a range of symptoms, and one of its effects when ingested in large amounts is the development of an **escharotic or corrosive effect** on the gastrointestinal mucosa. The presentation of an escharotic appearance of the oral cavity and the severe inflammation and gangrenous changes, especially in the cecum and large intestine, are consistent with mercury ingestion.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nArsenic poisoning typically causes symptoms like vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and can cause QT interval prolongation on ECG. It does not typically cause the intense inflammation and gangrene as described.\r\n\r\nSilver ingestion or exposure can result in argyria, which is a blue-gray discoloration of the skin but does not cause the described gastrointestinal effects.\r\n\r\nLead poisoning can cause neurological symptoms, anemia, and abdominal pain, commonly referred to as \"lead colic,\" but it does not produce the described escharotic effects or the intense inflammation and gangrene in the cecum and large intestine.\r\n\r\nCopper poisoning can lead to hemolytic anemia, jaundice, and renal failure. It can cause gastrointestinal symptoms like vomiting and diarrhea but does not typically cause the described oral or gastrointestinal effects.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 496","responses":[{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mercury","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5695,"text":"A 30-year-old man got hit on the vertex of the head that led to a fracture of the base of the skull. However, on examination, the bruise was found on the mastoid process behind the ears. What could be the reason for these positive findings of bruises on the mastoid processes?","explanation":"The presence of bruises on the mastoid processes (behind the ears) in a patient with a head injury involving a skull fracture is likely due to **gravitational shifting of blood.** \r\n\r\nIn cases of head trauma, particularly with skull fractures, blood can accumulate beneath the scalp, and its movement is influenced by gravity. As a result, blood can flow or shift to dependent areas, leading to the appearance of bruising or swelling in locations like the mastoid processes. This phenomenon is often referred to as **\"Battle's sign\"** when it occurs behind the ears and is associated with basilar skull fractures. It is a clinical sign that can be indicative of a skull fracture and may prompt further evaluation and imaging.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 400.","responses":[{"text":"Color of skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gravitational shifting of blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Birth mark","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vascularity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Due to natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5711,"text":"A 25-year-old man has noted cramping abdominal pain for the past week. On physical examination, there is right upper quadrant tenderness. Laboratory studies show increased serum transaminases. A liver biopsy was performed, and microscopic examination showed focal necrosis, interface inflammation with the extension of inflammation into the lobules from the portal triad. Which of the following is the most likely cause?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the patient's symptoms, including cramping abdominal pain, right upper quadrant tenderness, and increased serum transaminases is **viral hepatitis**. Histological findings of viral hepatitis include **focal necrosis** and **interface inflammation** with extension into the lobules from the portal triad.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 837.","responses":[{"text":"Viral hepatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eclampsia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxic injury by drugs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5842,"text":"A young girl is attacked by thieves who badly injure her with knives. On examination, the wounds are present on her body and arm, clearly cut with no bruising at the wound edges. Gaping is also noted at the edges. In light of the above findings, what is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Incised wounds** are typically characterized by **clean-cut, sharp edges**. They are often caused by sharp objects like knives or glass, and they tend to have minimal tissue damage beyond the immediate area of the cut. \r\n\r\n\r\nLacerations are wounds characterized by irregular, torn, or jagged edges. They are typically caused by blunt trauma, like a blow or a fall, where the skin and underlying tissue are forcefully stretched and torn. This differs from the clean-cut appearance described in the scenario.\r\n\r\nStab wounds are usually the result of a sharp, pointed object penetrating the skin. They often have a central entry point with less pronounced gaping compared to incised wounds.\r\n\r\nA contusion is essentially a bruise. Bruises result from blunt trauma that damages blood vessels beneath the skin, causing blood to leak into the surrounding tissue. They do not involve sharp-edged cuts or incisions.\r\n\r\nBruises are caused by blunt trauma that damages blood vessels, leading to the discoloration of the skin. They do not involve clear-cut, sharp edges or gaping.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stab wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incised wound","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5864,"text":"Antacid combinations of magnesium and aluminum salts are superior to single-component preparations because of which of the following reasons?","explanation":"Antacids that contain both magnesium and aluminum salts are often combined to counteract each other's potential side effects on bowel movements. **Magnesium-based antacids** tend to have a **laxative effect** and can lead to diarrhea, while **aluminum-based antacids** can result in **constipation**. \r\n\r\nWhen these two types of antacids are combined, their effects on bowel movements may balance out, reducing the likelihood of diarrhea or constipation.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Single agents avoid vomiting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents avoid gastric irritation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents are more likely to affect gastric emptying","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents are more likely alter bowel movement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents have rapid as well as sustained neutralizing action","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5912,"text":"A female patient comes to the clinic with complaints of diarrhea along with fever and abdominal cramping. Colonoscopy revealed pseudomembrane formation on colonic mucosa. The patient has a history of long-term intake of antibiotics. She still complains of repeated episodes of colitis. The doctor recommends fecal bacterio-therapy. Which one of the following bacteria is most probably involved?","explanation":"***Clostridium difficile*** is a bacterium responsible for causing antibiotic-associated colitis, including the **pseudomembranous colitis** seen in the patient. It typically occurs after a person has been taking antibiotics, which can disrupt the normal balance of gut bacteria. This disruption allows *C. difficile* to overgrow and produce toxins that lead to the characteristic symptoms of diarrhea, abdominal cramping, and fever.\r\n\r\nFecal microbiota transplantation (fecal bacterio-therapy) can be used as a treatment for recurrent *C. difficile* infection. It involves transplanting fecal matter from a healthy donor into the patient's colon to restore the normal balance of gut bacteria and eliminate the *C. difficile* infection. This therapy can be highly effective in cases of recurrent or severe *C. difficile*-associated colitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 791.","responses":[{"text":"Bacillus cereus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella dysenteriae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5913,"text":"What does free air under the diaphragm suggest?","explanation":"The presence of **free air under the diaphragm**, often seen on a medical imaging study like an X-ray or CT scan, is highly suggestive of **intestinal perforation**. When the wall of the gastrointestinal tract is compromised, such as in cases of a perforated ulcer, diverticulum, or other causes, air from within the digestive system can escape into the abdominal cavity. This air accumulates under the diaphragm, which is visible on imaging.\r\n\r\nIntestinal perforation can lead to a serious condition known as **peritonitis**, which is an inflammation of the peritoneum (the lining of the abdominal cavity). Immediate medical attention and surgical intervention are typically necessary in cases of intestinal perforation to address the underlying issue and prevent further complications.","reference":"Sureka B, Bansal K, Arora A. Pneumoperitoneum: What to look for in a radiograph? Journal of Family Medicine and Primary Care. Published 2015. Accessed July 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4535122/","responses":[{"text":"Paralytic ileus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal perforation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ruptured liver abscess","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5983,"text":"While examining a victim, the medicolegal officer writes a medicolegal certificate by mentioning a wound exposing bone without a fracture on the occipital area. How is this injury classified?","explanation":null,"reference":"Pakistan penal code. Accessed August 3, 2022. https://pljlawsite.com/html/ppc337a.htm","responses":[{"text":"Shajjah - I - Ammah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Khafifah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Munaquillah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Mudihah","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Damigah","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5989,"text":"Which of the following drugs prevents acid secretion by irreversibly binding to H+/K+ ATPase receptors?","explanation":"**Omeprazole** and other proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) work by **irreversibly** inhibiting the **H+/K+ ATPase proton pump** (also known as the gastric proton pump) in the stomach's parietal cells. This pump is responsible for the final step in the production of gastric acid. By binding to and inhibiting this pump, omeprazole reduces the production of stomach acid, making it effective in treating conditions associated with excess stomach acid, such as gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and peptic ulcers.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 1091-1092.","responses":[{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Octreotide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nizatidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminium hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6079,"text":"What causes post-operative paralytic ileus?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 361.\r\n\r\n(2) Beach EC, De Jesus O. Ileus. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed August 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558937/","responses":[{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6081,"text":"Which of the following correctly describes the glycemic index?","explanation":"The **glycemic index (GI)** is defined as the **ability of food to increase blood glucose levels** when compared to a reference carbohydrate, typically glucose or white bread. Foods with a high GI are rapidly digested and absorbed, leading to a quicker and larger increase in blood glucose levels, while foods with a low GI are digested and absorbed more slowly, resulting in a slower and smaller increase in blood glucose levels.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 366.\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Vlachos D, Malisova S, Lindberg FA, Karaniki G. Glycemic index (Gi) or glycemic load (Gl) and dietary interventions for optimizing postprandial hyperglycemia in patients with t2 diabetes: a review. Nutrients. Published May 27, 2020. Accessed August 7, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7352659/","responses":[{"text":"The ability of food to increase blood glucose levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of food to reduce blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of the liver to increase blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of the liver to maintain blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of the liver to reduce blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6115,"text":"A friction burn is which type of injury?","explanation":"A **friction burn** is considered an **abrasion**. It is a type of injury that occurs when the skin is rubbed or scraped against a rough surface, causing damage to the outer layer of the skin. Abrasions are often superficial and result in the removal of the skin's topmost layer.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 189-190.","responses":[{"text":"Abrasion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chop wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slash wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laceration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6121,"text":"Which of the following is a chemical asphyxiant?","explanation":"**Carbon monoxide gas** is a chemical **asphyxiant**. It interferes with the body's ability to transport oxygen in the blood, leading to oxygen deprivation in the body's tissues and organs. Carbon monoxide poisoning can be life-threatening. The other gases mentioned, such as mustard gas, nitric oxide gas, phosgene gas, and nitrogen dioxide gas, have toxic effects but do not primarily act as chemical asphyxiants.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 586.","responses":[{"text":"Nitrogen dioxide gas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosgene gas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon monoxide gas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric oxide gas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mustard gas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6130,"text":"What color precipitate is formed after adding 3% tannic acid to blood samples containing carboxyhemoglobin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 681.","responses":[{"text":"Pink","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Purple","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cherry red","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Black","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"White","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10373,"text":"Which of the following is a side effect of ribavirin?","explanation":"**Hemolytic anemia** is a known side effect of ribavirin. **Ribavirin** is an antiviral medication used in the treatment of certain viral infections, including hepatitis C. One of its side effects is the potential to cause hemolytic anemia, a condition where red blood cells are destroyed faster than they can be produced, leading to a reduced red blood cell count. This can result in symptoms such as fatigue, pallor, and shortness of breath.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 891.","responses":[{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutropenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constipation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10379,"text":"On colonoscopy, a surgeon will differentiate the jejunum from ileum by which of the following?","explanation":"The following are the distinguishing features of jejunum and ileum:\r\n\r\nLength and thickness: The jejunum is typically located more proximally (closer to the stomach) than the ileum and is longer, about 2.5 meters. In contrast, the ileum is shorter, measuring approximately 3.6 meters. It is wider and **thicker than the ileum**.\r\n\r\n Vasa recta: The jejunum has **longer vasa recta** (straight arteries in the mesentery) compared to the ileum. The ileum has shorter vasa recta.\r\n\r\n Arterial arcades: The jejunum has **fewer arterial arcades**, while the ileum has more complex arterial arcades.\r\n\r\n Mesenteric fat: The jejunum typically has **less mesenteric fat**, making it appear redder and more vascular, while the ileum has more mesenteric fat, giving it a paler appearance.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 311.\r\n\r\n(2) Knipe H. Jejunum vs ileum | radiology reference article | radiopaedia. Org. Radiopaedia. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/jejunum-vs-ileum-1","responses":[{"text":"Jejunum has shorter vasa recta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has more mesenteric fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has thinner wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has fewer arterial arcades","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has narrower lumen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10381,"text":"While circulating in the blood, copper largely binds to which of the following proteins?","explanation":"**Copper** largely binds to ceruloplasmin, which is a copper-transporting protein. **Ceruloplasmin** is the major copper-carrying protein in the blood and plays a crucial role in copper homeostasis. It also serves as an enzyme and an antioxidant, among other functions.\r\n---\r\n\r\nAlbumin: It primarily serves as a carrier for many substances, including hormones, fatty acids, and some drugs, but it is not the primary carrier for copper.\r\n\r\nTransferrin: Transferrin is a transport protein that mainly carries iron in the blood, not copper.\r\n\r\nHaptoglobin: Haptoglobin is another blood protein, but its primary role is to bind and remove free hemoglobin that is released into the bloodstream from red blood cells. It is not involved in copper transport.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 80.","responses":[{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceruloplasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10382,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding split laceration?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 195.","responses":[{"text":"It occurs due to sudden compression between two hard objects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can occur on the forehead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can occur on the scrotal skin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It looks like an incised wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a type of laceration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10392,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a stab wound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200, 201.","responses":[{"text":"Its greatest dimension is depth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It results from piercing with a pointed weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may occur with a knife","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a wedge shaped opening wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In this injury bruising around the opening of the wound is seen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10399,"text":"What is a stab wound defined as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200.","responses":[{"text":"The tearing or splitting of skin, mucous membranes, muscles or internal organs caused by either a shearing or a crushing force","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A clean cut wound through the tissues, which is more long than deep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetration with long narrow, usually pointed, object that is deeper than its length and width","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous/subepithelial tissues due to rupture of blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Any injury with breach in natural continuity of skin or mucous membranes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10401,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding age and color of a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Normal at 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Green on day 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue on day 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow on day 7-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Depends on size and swelling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10402,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding hepatorenal syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Medicine slides, Topic: Ascites and concept of SAAG.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium avidity is the culprit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Laboratory finding consistent with post-renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dialysis is the mainstay treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 develops more slowly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diagnosed when serum creatinine \u003c 1.5 despite using diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10652,"text":"Transport of glucose across the basolateral membrane in intestinal cells occurs through which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hantzidiamantis PJ, Lappin SL. Physiology, glucose. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed September 18, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545201/","responses":[{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+/glucose transporter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11409,"text":"A person presents to the emergency department with chronic diarrhea and abdominal pain for months. Findings show aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures occupying the ascending and transverse colon but sparing the rectum and descending colon with skipped areas with excess fat creeping over mucosa. Cryptitis is also seen in lamina propria along with non-caseating granulomas. Which is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"The presentation includes chronic diarrhea and abdominal pain along with specific findings such as aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures, and non-caseating granulomas in the lamina propria. These features are indicative of **Crohn's disease**. One of the hallmark characteristics of Crohn's is the presence of **\"skipped areas\"** of affected tissue, which contrasts with **ulcerative colitis** that usually shows continuous inflammation.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nLactose intolerance primarily causes diarrhea and bloating but does not lead to the aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures, or non-caseating granulomas described in the question. Whipple disease is a systemic illness affecting multiple organs and is associated with a bacteria called *Tropheryma whipplei*; it would not specifically lead to the findings described.\r\n\r\nCeliac disease is an autoimmune disorder primarily affecting the small intestine in response to gluten intake and is characterized by villous atrophy rather than cryptitis and non-caseating granulomas.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Lactose intolerance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Whipple disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11964,"text":"Hepatic encephalopathy is a spectrum of disturbances in consciousness, ranging from subtle behavioral abnormalities to marked confusion and stupor, to deep coma and death. Which of the following is a useful indicator of its prognosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 826.","responses":[{"text":"Prothrombin time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma sodium levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum ammonia levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11980,"text":"Which of the following is a cause of bleeding in subdural hematoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 245.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cerebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diploic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bridging and communicating veins","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12006,"text":"Which of the following arteries passes behind the first part of the duodenum?","explanation":null,"reference":"Gastroduodenal Artery - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/gastroduodenal-artery. Accessed 20 Aug. 2022.","responses":[{"text":"Pancreaticoduodenal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroduodenal artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12746,"text":"Which of the following colonic polyps is not premalignant?","explanation":"**Juvenile polyps** are not typically premalignant when they are sporadic or isolated.\r\n\r\nJuvenile polyps are a type of hamartomatous polyp typically found in children, usually in the rectum. They are generally benign and are not associated with a significant risk of malignant transformation when they are isolated.\r\n\r\nWhile sporadic juvenile polyps are usually benign, multiple juvenile polyps can be seen in juvenile polyposis syndrome, which does carry an increased risk of colorectal cancer.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, villous adenoma, tubular adenoma, and tubulo-villous adenoma are adenomatous polyps and have malignant potential. Hamartomatous polyps associated with Peutz-Jeghers syndrome also have an increased risk of malignancy.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Pathology, Topic: MCQ's Tumors of small and long intestine, Sub-topic: Question 18.","responses":[{"text":"Juvenile polyps","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hamartomatous polyps associated with Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubulo-villous adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubular adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12747,"text":"What type of food may cause colon cancer?","explanation":"**Red meat and processed meat** have been associated with an increased risk of colon cancer.\r\n\r\nAccording to the World Health Organization (WHO) and the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC), processed meat is classified as Group 1 (carcinogenic to humans), which means there is sufficient evidence that processed meat can cause colorectal cancer. Red meat, which includes beef, lamb, and pork, is categorized as Group 2A (probably carcinogenic to humans), indicating limited evidence from human studies but sufficient evidence from animal studies.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 828.","responses":[{"text":"Caffeine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fizzy drinks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leafy vegetables","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dairy products","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red meat and processed meat","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12748,"text":"Which of the following is the most common clinical presentation of Meckel diverticulum?","explanation":"The most common clinical presentation of Meckel diverticulum is **gastrointestinal bleeding**.\r\n\r\nMeckel diverticulum is a congenital anomaly resulting from the incomplete obliteration of the omphalomesenteric (vitelline) duct. In children, especially those under the age of 2, gastrointestinal bleeding is the most common symptom, often resulting from the presence of ectopic gastric mucosa in the diverticulum that secretes acid. This acid secretion can lead to ulceration of the adjacent ileal mucosa, which causes the bleeding. In many cases, especially in adults, Meckel diverticulum is asymptomatic and may be discovered incidentally during imaging or surgery for other reasons.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 825.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrointestinal bleeding","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermittent abdominal pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diverticulitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal perforation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12749,"text":"Which of the following is the most common site of adenocarcinoma in the small intestine?","explanation":"The most common site of adenocarcinoma in the small intestine is the **duodenum**. \r\n\r\nAlthough primary small bowel cancers are relatively rare compared to other gastrointestinal malignancies, when they do occur, the duodenum is the most frequent site for adenocarcinomas within the small intestine.","reference":"Anzidei M, Napoli A, Zini C, Kirchin MA, Catalano C, Passariello R. Malignant tumours of the small intestine: a review of histopathology, multidetector CT and MRI aspects. The British Journal of Radiology. Published August 2011. Accessed January 11, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3473441/","responses":[{"text":"Meckel diverticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyps","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12750,"text":"Which of the following is the most common tumor of the small intestine?","explanation":"The most common tumor of the small intestine is the **carcinoid tumor**.\r\n\r\nWhile adenocarcinomas are the most common type of malignant tumor in most parts of the gastrointestinal tract, within the small intestine, carcinoid tumors predominate. These are neuroendocrine tumors that can secrete various substances, sometimes leading to the carcinoid syndrome in certain conditions.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Pathology, Topic: MCQ's Tumors of small and long intestine, Sub-topic: Question 5.","responses":[{"text":"Choristoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoid tumor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MALToma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12751,"text":"Which of the following is true about ulcerative colitis with colon cancer?","explanation":"Patients with ulcerative colitis have an **increased risk** of developing colon cancer, and this risk is related to the **duration and extent of the disease**. Generally, the risk of cancer begins to increase significantly after about 8-10 years of disease and continues to rise over time. Regular surveillance colonoscopies are recommended for patients with long-standing ulcerative colitis to detect dysplasia or early cancers.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 804.","responses":[{"text":"It is related to the duration of ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a better prognosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is related to disease activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignancy is more in anorectal ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It arises in pseudo polyps","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12752,"text":"Gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) are more commonly found at which of the following locations on the gastrointestinal tract?","explanation":"**Gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs)** can occur anywhere along the gastrointestinal (GI) tract, but the most common location is the stomach, followed by the **small intestine**. Less commonly, they can be found in the colon, rectum, and esophagus.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Pathology, Topic: MCQ's Tumors of small and long intestine, Sub-topic: Question 14.","responses":[{"text":"Small intestine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cecum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesentery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sigmoid colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12766,"text":"While repairing the ileum for a stab wound in a 31-year-old man, a 1 cm circumscribed submucosal mass in the ileum is noticed. Microscopically, the mass is composed of nests of cells with uniform small round nuclei and cytoplasm with small purple granules. The cytoplasm is positive with an antibody to chromogranin. Which of the following pathologic findings is most likely to accompany this man's lesion?","explanation":"The lesion described in the ileum, with its nests of cells containing **small round nuclei** and **cytoplasmic granules** that are **chromogranin-positive**, is characteristic of a carcinoid tumor. Carcinoid tumors are neuroendocrine tumors that can secrete various peptides and amines. \r\n\r\nThe most common associated finding with an ileal carcinoid tumor is the presence of **another similar lesion** in the ileum. Ileal carcinoid tumors are usually multiple.\r\n\r\nMultiple gastric ulcerations are associated with gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison syndrome). Inflammatory bowel disease can be associated with increased risk of colorectal cancer, not carcinoid tumor. Liver metastases can occur with larger carcinoid tumors, but small tumors are usually benign. Pancreatic adenocarcinoma is not associated with ileal carcinoid tumors.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 819.","responses":[{"text":"Liver metastases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Another similar lesion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple gastric ulcerations","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12767,"text":"A 20-year-old man is healthy but has a family history of colon cancer with onset at a young age. No abnormal physical examination findings are observed. On colonoscopy, there are over 200 tubular adenomas ranging in size from 0.2 to 1 cm on gross inspection. Which of the following genetic diseases is the man most likely to have?","explanation":"The man most likely has **adenomatous polyposis coli (APC)**, also known as familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP). FAP is an autosomal dominant condition characterized by the presence of hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps in the colon. These polyps usually begin to appear in the teenage years. If untreated, virtually all patients with FAP will develop colorectal cancer, typically by the fourth decade of life. The disease is caused by mutations in the APC gene.\r\n\r\nPeutz-Jeghers syndrome presents with hamartomatous polyps and is associated with mucocutaneous pigmentation.\r\n\r\nPTEN-associated syndrome (like Cowden syndrome) leads to multiple hamartomas.\r\n\r\nHereditary nonpolyposis colorectal carcinoma syndrome (Lynch syndrome) has an increased risk for colon cancer but does not show numerous adenomas as seen in FAP.\r\n\r\nMultiple endocrine neoplasia syndromes primarily affect endocrine organs.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812.","responses":[{"text":"PTEN-associated syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal carcinoma syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenomatous polyposis coli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple endocrine neoplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12768,"text":"A 30-year-old woman presents to the clinic with the complaint of a swollen, red, and painful left knee for the past two weeks. She has a 7-month history of bloody diarrhea and crampy abdominal pain. Abdominal palpation reveals tenderness over the left lower quadrant. Labs show a hemoglobin level of 9.3 g/dL. Microscopic examination of her stool reveals occult blood. A diffusely red, bleeding, friable colonic mucosa is visualized by colonoscopy. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Ulcerative colitis (UC)** is an inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) characterized by chronic inflammation of the colonic mucosa. Common symptoms include bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, and tenesmus. It can also present with extraintestinal manifestations, such as arthritis (as in the swollen, painful knee described), erythema nodosum, uveitis, and primary sclerosing cholangitis, among others. The inflammation in UC is continuous and starts from the rectum and extends proximally. Colonoscopy typically reveals a **diffusely inflamed, friable**, and bleeding mucosa. \r\n\r\nCarcinoid tumor typically presents with flushing, diarrhea, and bronchospasm in advanced disease with liver metastases.\r\n\r\nCrohn disease can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus and often spares some segments, leading to \"skip\" lesions. Transmural inflammation can lead to strictures and fistulas.\r\n\r\nAdenocarcinoma can be a complication of long-standing ulcerative colitis but does not match the described presentation.\r\n\r\nPseudomembranous colitis, typically caused by *Clostridium difficile*, presents with watery diarrhea following antibiotic use and would be associated with yellowish plaques on colonoscopy.","reference":"(1)Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 110.\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Pseudomembranous colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoid tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12769,"text":"A 54-year-old alcoholic male presents with sudden onset of severe, constant epigastric pain that radiates to his mid-back. Further evaluation finds fever, steatorrhea, and discoloration around his flank and umbilicus. Lab investigations reveal elevated serum levels of amylase and lipase. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Acute pancreatitis** presents with sudden onset of **severe epigastric pain** that often radiates to the back. The pain is often associated with nausea and vomiting. The presence of elevated serum levels of amylase and lipase is diagnostic. Alcoholism, as in this patient, is one of the major causes of acute pancreatitis. The discoloration around the flank (**Grey Turner's sign**) and umbilicus (**Cullen's sign**) are due to the leakage of pancreatic enzymes into the retroperitoneal space and peritoneal cavity, respectively, leading to the breakdown of hemoglobin and the appearance of ecchymosis. These signs indicate severe pancreatitis with a worse prognosis.\r\n\r\nAcute diverticulitis typically presents with left lower quadrant abdominal pain.\r\n\r\nAcute appendicitis usually presents with right lower quadrant pain.\r\n\r\nAcute cholangitis is characterized by right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, and fever (Charcot's triad).\r\n\r\nAcute cholecystitis typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, fever, and a positive Murphy's sign.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 115.","responses":[{"text":"Acute diverticulitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12770,"text":"A 65-year-old male is operated on for the removal of a pancreatic lesion. The patient's history includes an episode of acute pancreatitis two years prior. The most likely histological feature on microscopic examination is the presence of which of the following?","explanation":"The most likely histological feature for this patient, given the history of acute pancreatitis followed by the development of a pancreatic lesion, is a **pancreatic pseudocyst**.\r\n\r\nPancreatic pseudocysts are complications that can arise after an episode of acute pancreatitis. They are essentially collections of pancreatic secretions enclosed by a wall of granulation tissue, but they lack an epithelial lining, which differentiates them from true cysts. \r\n\r\nMucinous cyst and mucinous cystadenoma are true cystic neoplasms with mucinous epithelial lining and have malignant potential.\r\n\r\nCholedochal cysts are congenital dilatations of the biliary tree.\r\n\r\nSerous cystadenomas are benign cystic tumors of the pancreas filled with clear serous fluid. They are typically microcystic and have a characteristic \"honeycomb\" appearance on imaging.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 888.","responses":[{"text":"Serous cystadenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucinous cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucinous cystadenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choldedocal cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic pseudocyst","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12773,"text":"A 9-year-old child presents with a prolonged history of abdominal discomfort, bloating, constipation, weight loss, and anemia. Serological examination shows positivity for anti-endomysial antibodies. An endoscopic biopsy of the jejunum will most likely show which of the following features?","explanation":"The child's presentation is suggestive of celiac disease, an autoimmune condition triggered by ingestion of gluten in genetically predisposed individuals. The characteristic histological feature of celiac disease on jejunal biopsy is **villous atrophy**.\r\n\r\nPseudomembrane refers to a layer of exudate that can be found in conditions like pseudomembranous colitis, typically caused by *Clostridium difficile* infection. This is not associated with celiac disease.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Periodic Acid-Schiff (PAS) stain is used to detect polysaccharides such as glycogen and mucosubstances such as glycoproteins, glycolipids and mucins in tissues. This staining feature is associated with certain conditions like Whipple's disease, which causes a buildup of PAS-positive foamy macrophages in the small intestine. This is not seen in celiac disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 785.","responses":[{"text":"Loss of goblet cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PAS-postive granules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous expansion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous atrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomembrane","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12775,"text":"A 30-year-old female is prescribed a broad-spectrum antibiotic for a severe upper respiratory tract infection. After a few days, the respiratory symptoms improve but the patient now develops abdominal cramps, watery diarrhea, and dehydration. Which of the following organisms is the most likely cause of this patient's condition?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms suggest antibiotic-associated diarrhea, specifically **pseudomembranous colitis**. The most likely causative organism for pseudomembranous colitis is ***Clostridium difficile*** (often abbreviated as C. diff). \r\n\r\nWhen broad-spectrum antibiotics are taken, they can disrupt the normal bacterial flora of the colon, allowing overgrowth of *C. difficile*. This bacterium releases toxins that lead to inflammation of the colon and the described symptoms.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 793.","responses":[{"text":"Tropheryma whipplei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium botulinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella paratyphi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella typhi","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12776,"text":"Patients suffering from ulcerative colitis are at risk of suffering from which of the following conditions?","explanation":"Patients with **ulcerative colitis**, especially those with extensive disease or a longer duration of disease, are at an increased risk for developing **colorectal cancer (adenocarcinoma)**.\r\n\r\n**Granulomatous lymphadenitis** is not specifically associated with ulcerative colitis.\r\n  \r\nFistula formation is more commonly associated with Crohn's disease, another type of inflammatory bowel disease, than with ulcerative colitis.\r\n  \r\n**Intra-abdominal adhesions** are more commonly seen after abdominal surgeries or with conditions that involve the entire bowel wall, such as Crohn's disease.\r\n  \r\nWhile strictures can occur in UC, true intestinal obstructions are more common in Crohn's disease due to transmural inflammation leading to strictures.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 839.","responses":[{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intra-abdominal adhesions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous lymphadenitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fistula","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12778,"text":"Which of the following is not a specific feature of dysentery?","explanation":"Dysentery typically presents with frequent, small volume stools that may contain blood, mucus, and pus. The predominant symptoms are abdominal pain and cramping, frequent urge to defecate, and the passage of bloody and/or mucoid stools.\r\n\r\nDespite the frequent urge to defecate, the actual volume of stool passed in dysentery is typically low.\r\n\r\nDysentery is commonly caused by infectious agents, such as certain strains of bacteria (e.g., Shigella, certain strains of Escherichia coli) or parasites (e.g., Entamoeba histolytica).\r\n\r\nDysentery is often associated with abdominal pain and cramping. Patient experiences perianal discomfort. This can occur due to the frequent passage of stools and the presence of irritative substances like blood and pus in the stool.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 784, 789.","responses":[{"text":"The stools are low volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"There is an increase in stool mass","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It has an infectious etiology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient experiences perianal discomfort","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a painful condition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12780,"text":"Which of the following is the watershed zone?","explanation":"The **splenic flexure** is considered the watershed zone. It is also referred to as Griffith's point. A \"watershed\" area is a region of an organ (in this case, the colon) that has **dual blood supply** and is, therefore, at greater risk of ischemia under conditions of decreased blood flow. The splenic flexure of the colon receives blood from the most distal branches of both the superior mesenteric artery and the inferior mesenteric artery, making it vulnerable to ischemic conditions.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 781.","responses":[{"text":"Descending colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic flexure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transverse colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cecum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12787,"text":"A 32-year-old man with hepatitis B refractory to treatments has begun an oral course of lamivudine. The mechanism of action of this medication likely involves which of the following?","explanation":"**Lamivudine** is a nucleoside analog reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NRTI). It is used in the treatment of chronic hepatitis B and HIV infections. In the context of hepatitis B, it works by inhibiting the reverse transcription of the viral RNA pregenome to DNA by acting as a competitive inhibitor and chain terminator of the viral reverse transcriptase, which is an enzyme that the hepatitis B virus (HBV) uses to replicate its DNA, i.e., **HBV DNA polymerase**.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 439.","responses":[{"text":"HBV DNA polymerase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HBV RNA transferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBV DNA transferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBV RNA polymerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBV DNA synthetase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12790,"text":"A 58-year-old man with a history of occasional GERD presents to the clinic with diarrhea for the past 3 months. He has not been sick and has been feeling quite well otherwise. Which of the following antacids is the most likely to prevent episodes of diarrhea?","explanation":"Antacids are agents that neutralize the stomach acid and can cause various side effects depending on their composition:\r\n\r\n1. **Sodium bicarbonate**: Can lead to systemic alkalosis if taken in large amounts.\r\n2. **Magnesium hydroxide**: Often causes diarrhea.\r\n3. **Bismuth**: Can cause a dark stool but is not typically used solely as an antacid.\r\n4. **Calcium carbonate**: Can cause constipation and, in excessive amounts, can also lead to hypercalcemia.\r\n5. **Aluminium hydroxide**: Often causes constipation.\r\n\r\nGiven the patient's complaint of diarrhea, an antacid that may help prevent further episodes by causing a counter effect would be **aluminium hydroxide**, as it typically causes **constipation**.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 498.","responses":[{"text":"Bismuth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium carbonate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminium hydroxide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12794,"text":"A 28-year-old female patient is brought to the emergency department with the complaint of severe generalized body pain for the past 1 day that is associated with vomiting. She has also not passed any stool for the past 2 days. She has had colicky abdominal pain for the past 3 months and has lost a significant amount of weight. She has a pulse of 120 beats per minute, blood pressure of 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate of 32 breaths per minute, and she is afebrile. She has a distended tense tender abdomen with a tympanic note and her gut sounds are inaudible. What would be the most appropriate radiological investigation to reach a diagnosis for this patient?","explanation":"The patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with an **acute bowel obstruction**, as evidenced by the colicky abdominal pain, vomiting, abdominal distension, and the absence of stool passage.\r\n\r\nIn the setting of an acute bowel obstruction, plain abdominal radiography can provide important diagnostic information. **X-ray abdomen erect** (or upright) can demonstrate air-fluid levels, which are characteristic of bowel obstruction. The upright view is also important to detect any free intraperitoneal air (indicative of perforation).\r\n\r\nGiven that she is in an emergency setting with acute symptoms and has had a history of colicky abdominal pain and weight loss (possibly suggesting a chronic process leading to the acute obstruction, such as a tumor or inflammatory stricture), the **X-ray abdomen erect** would be the most appropriate initial radiological investigation. If the findings are inconclusive, or if further information is needed after the plain films, a CT scan of the abdomen would be the next step.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 190.","responses":[{"text":"X-ray abdomen supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen erect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT-scan abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12795,"text":"A 37-year-old female with mild arthritis presents to the clinic for a follow-up. She states that she is doing much better because of doubling her dose of ibuprofen. The physician warns the patient about peptic ulcers and bleeding from taking too much ibuprofen. She is offered alternatives, but the patient refuses because the ibuprofen works so well. What is the most appropriate therapy for this patient to prevent peptic ulcers?","explanation":"**Misoprostol** is a prostaglandin E1 analog that helps reduce the risk of NSAID-induced gastric ulcers. It can be used prophylactically in patients who are at high risk of complications from NSAIDs, particularly those with a previous history of ulcers or those who require high doses of NSAIDs.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBismuth is often used as part of a regimen to treat Helicobacter pylori infections, and it can also have some protective effects on the stomach lining.\r\n\r\nFamotidine is an H2 receptor antagonist that reduces acid production in the stomach. It can be used for treating conditions like gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) or ulcers.\r\n\r\nLansoprazole is a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) that significantly reduces acid production. PPIs are also commonly used to reduce the risk of NSAID-induced ulcers, especially in high-risk patients.\r\n\r\nPirenzepine is an M1 selective antimuscarinic agent and is typically not the first choice for preventing NSAID-induced ulcers.\r\n\r\nMany clinicians nowadays prefer proton pump inhibitors like lansoprazole because they are better tolerated than misoprostol (which can cause diarrhea).","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Pirenzepine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Famotidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lonsoprazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bismuth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13195,"text":"A 21-year-old male presented to the emergency department with a complaint of colicky abdominal pain off-and-on along with low-grade evening fever for the past 3 months. He has had vomiting for the past 2 days and absolute constipation for 1 day. He has lost 7 kg in the last 3 months. He is anemic, dehydrated, has a pulse of 100 beats per minute, blood pressure of 100 mmHg, and weight of 40 kg. His abdomen is distended and is tympanic on auscultation with tenderness. Gut sounds are inaudible. What would be the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Tuberculous peritonitis** is a form of extrapulmonary tuberculosis that affects the peritoneum. Patients often present with non-specific abdominal symptoms such as pain, ascites, and fever. Weight loss is also a common feature. It is an important differential diagnosis in regions where tuberculosis is endemic, especially in young patients presenting with these features.\r\n\r\nChemical peritonitis usually occurs after rupture of an organ that releases irritating substances into the peritoneal cavity, such as a ruptured ovarian cyst releasing its content.\r\n\r\nAcute pancreatitis presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back and may be associated with a history of gallstones or heavy alcohol intake. Elevated serum amylase and lipase would also be suggestive.\r\n\r\nDuodenal perforation would present acutely with severe pain, and signs of chemical and then bacterial peritonitis would be evident. It can be a complication of peptic ulcer disease.\r\n\r\nEnteric perforation (like from typhoid fever) could present similarly, but the clinical context and other accompanying symptoms would help differentiate it from tuberculous peritonitis.","reference":"Bailey and love, 27th edition, page 1053-54","responses":[{"text":"Enteric perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical peritonitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculous peritonitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13196,"text":"A 32-year-old female presents with the complaint of crampy abdominal pain and loose stools for the past 1 month with a frequency of 6-8/day. The stool was mixed with mucus and blood, with occasional blood clots seen. On examination, she has pallor and is lethargic. Her abdomen is tender in the right and left iliac fossa. A digital rectal examination shows a blood-stained finger with stool.  Stool culture yields negative for any growth. Colonoscopy shows diffuse erythema of the entire colon with ulceration and spontaneous bleeding. Histopathology shows an increase in inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. The walls of the crypts of Lieberkuhn are infiltrated by inflammatory cells and there are crypt abscesses. What would be the most likely diagnosis in her case?","explanation":"**Ulcerative colitis (UC)** is a form of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that primarily affects the colon. It is characterized by:\r\n\r\n1. Diffuse and continuous inflammation, typically starting from the rectum and extending proximally.\r\n2. Clinical symptoms of abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea.\r\n3. Colonoscopic findings of diffuse erythema, ulceration, and spontaneous bleeding.\r\n4. Histopathological findings of inflammation predominantly limited to the mucosa, with the presence of **cryptitis** and **crypt abscesses**.\r\n\r\n\r\nCrohn's disease\r\ncan affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract and is associated with \"skip lesions\", transmural inflammation, and granulomas on biopsy, which differentiate it from UC.\r\n\r\nAmoebic colitis is caused by the parasite *Entamoeba histolytica*. Its diagnosis is often supported by stool tests showing the parasite or serology.\r\n\r\nYersinia colitis would likely show the organism on culture, and its histopathological features are distinct from UC.\r\n\r\n*Clostridium difficile* infection is typically seen after antibiotic usage and can be confirmed by detecting the toxin in the stool.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 835-837.","responses":[{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Yersinia colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoebic colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13204,"text":"A 50-year-old caucasian male presents to the clinic with post-prandial abdominal pain, watery diarrhea, frequent oral aphthous ulceration, and weight loss for the past 6 months. He was advised upper gastrointestinal (GI) endoscopy and colonoscopy by a family physician. The endoscopic appearance is suggestive of cobblestone. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Crohn disease** is a type of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from the mouth to the anus. The symptoms mentioned are consistent with the disease, including post-prandial abdominal pain, watery diarrhea, oral aphthous ulcers, and weight loss. Additionally, the endoscopic appearance of a \"cobblestone\" pattern is a hallmark of Crohn disease, which results from deep ulcerations interspersed with normal or edematous mucosa.\r\n\r\nAmoebic colitis is caused by *Entamoeba histolytica* and usually presents with bloody diarrhea, and the diagnosis can be made by identifying the parasite in the stool.\r\n\r\nUlcerative colitis is another form of IBD, but it affects only the colon and rectum and is characterized by continuous inflammation, in contrast to the \"skip lesions\" seen in Crohn disease.\r\n\r\nShigellosis is an acute bacterial infection causing dysentery with blood and mucus in the stool.\r\n\r\nIschemic colitis results from decreased blood flow to the colon and can present with abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, but its endoscopic appearance would be different from the cobblestone pattern seen in Crohn disease.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 837.","responses":[{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigellosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoebic colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic colitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13205,"text":"A 50-year-old male has been a known case of ulcerative colitis (biopsy proven) for the last 20 years with in-frequent flare-ups in between. He is currently stable on an aminosalicylic acid (5-ASA) regimen. What is the chance of colorectal malignancy in this case?","explanation":"In patients with ulcerative colitis, the risk of developing colorectal malignancy is closely tied to the duration of the disease. The longer a person has ulcerative colitis, the higher their likelihood of developing cancer. \r\n\r\n- At 10 years, the risk stands at roughly 1%. \r\n- At 20 years, the risk significantly rises to between **10 and 15%**. \r\n- At 30 years, the risk is up to 20%.\r\n\r\nGiven this patient's **20-year history** of biopsy-proven ulcerative colitis, his risk of developing colorectal malignancy is estimated to be between **10% and 15%**.","reference":"(1) O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, Sayers RD, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2023: 1320.\r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 839.","responses":[{"text":"5% - 7%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10% - 15%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"5% - 10%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20% - 25%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1% - 5%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13206,"text":"A 30-year-old woman who has a history of ulcerative colitis for the past 5 years develops severe lower gastrointestinal bleeding necessitating blood transfusions frequently in the last 15 days. She is advised to undergo surgery on an emergent basis. What should be the ideal procedure in this case?","explanation":"For a patient with ulcerative colitis who has developed **severe lower gastrointestinal bleeding**, necessitating frequent blood transfusions, a prompt surgical intervention is required. In the acute setting described, especially with severe bleeding, the priority is to control the bleeding and stabilize the patient. **Subtotal colectomy with end-ileostomy** achieves this by removing the majority of the colon, which is the source of the bleeding, and diverting the fecal stream to an external bag, allowing the rectum to heal. It provides immediate relief and stabilization and can be followed later by more definitive procedures, if necessary.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n **Total abdominal colectomy with ileal anastomosis (TAC-IRA)** removes the entire colon but leaves the rectum intact, connecting the end of the small intestine (ileum) directly to the rectum. This procedure can be used for ulcerative colitis but may not be ideal in an emergency setting due to the bleeding risk from the retained rectum.\r\n\r\n**Total proctocolectomy with end ileostomy** removes the entire colon and the rectum, resulting in a permanent ileostomy. It is a definitive surgical treatment for ulcerative colitis but might be considered more aggressive than necessary in the described scenario.\r\n\r\n**Restorative proctocolectomy with ileal pouch anal anastomosis (RPC-IPAA)** involves the removal of the entire colon and the rectum, with the creation of an internal pouch from the small intestine, which is then connected to the anus. It allows the patient to have bowel movements without an external bag. This procedure is popular for treating ulcerative colitis as it preserves bowel continuity, but it requires multiple stages and may not be appropriate in the acute setting described.\r\n\r\n**Segmental resection of diseased bowel** involves removing only the affected portion of the colon. However, because ulcerative colitis usually involves the entire colon in a continuous manner, segmental resection is not a standard treatment for ulcerative colitis.","reference":"(1) O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, Sayers RD, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2023: 1323-1324.\r\n \r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 844.","responses":[{"text":"Restorative proctocolectomy with ileal pouch anal anastomosis (RPC-IPAA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total abdominal colectomy with ileal anastomosis (TAC-IRA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subtotal colectomy and ileostomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Total proctocolectomy with end ileostomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Segmental resection of diseased bowel","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13208,"text":"A 40-year-old female presents to the emergency department with severe pain in her right upper abdomen for the past 1 day. Pain radiated toward her right shoulder. On examination, she is febrile and has a severely tender right hypochondrium. Lab investigations show Hb 10 mg/dL and a total leukocyte count of 15,000/mm³. The remainder of her investigations are all normal. Ultrasound shows increased wall thickness of the gall bladder. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The patient's presentation is consistent with **acute cholecystitis**. She has severe **pain in her right upper abdomen** that radiates towards her right shoulder, a common presentation for gallbladder pathology due to referred pain from the diaphragmatic irritation. The fever and elevated white blood cell count indicate an inflammatory or infectious process. Furthermore, the ultrasound findings of an increased **gallbladder wall thickness** further support this diagnosis.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPancreatitis would typically present with severe pain radiating to the back, along with elevated amylase and lipase levels, which are not mentioned in the given scenario.\r\n\r\nRenal colic is typically characterized by flank pain that can radiate to the groin and is often associated with hematuria.\r\n\r\nAcute appendicitis typically presents with pain that begins around the navel and then shifts to the right lower quadrant of the abdomen.\r\n\r\nCholelithiasis, which is the presence of stones in the gallbladder, can cause pain (biliary colic) but does not by itself cause fever or leukocytosis.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 915.","responses":[{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal colic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13209,"text":"A 15-year-old male presented to the emergency department with severe pain in his right lower abdomen for the past 1 hour. The pain was initially around the umbilicus but it has now radiated toward the right lower abdomen. The pain gets worse with movement. He is febrile, tachycardic, tachypneic, and has a narrow pulse pressure. He has a tender right iliac fossa with the presence of rebound tenderness. Lab investigations show Hb 15 mg/dL and a total leukocyte count of 25,000/mm³. The remainder of the investigations is all normal. Ultrasound shows a non-compressible tubular structure in the right iliac fossa and fluid in the pelvis. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The patient's clinical presentation is indicative of **acute appendicitis**. The classical presentation starts with pain around the umbilicus, which then shifts to the right lower quadrant (RLQ) of the abdomen. Tenderness in the right iliac fossa, particularly with rebound tenderness, supports the diagnosis of acute appendicitis. A high white blood cell count (leukocytosis) is also commonly seen in appendicitis due to the body's inflammatory response. The ultrasound findings of a non-compressible tubular structure in the right iliac fossa and fluid in the pelvis further support the diagnosis, indicating an inflamed appendix and possible associated local inflammation or small localized collection.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPerforated gallbladder would typically present with pain in the right upper quadrant, not the RLQ. \r\n\r\nPerforated appendix is a complication of untreated or advanced appendicitis. This condition can lead to generalized peritonitis, but the primary diagnosis, in this case, remains appendicitis. \r\n\r\nAcute cholecystitis involves inflammation of the gallbladder and would present with pain in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen, not the RLQ.\r\n\r\nRuptured diverticulum would be quite unusual in a 15-year-old, as diverticulosis and its complications (like diverticulitis or rupture) are more common in older adults.","reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1303.","responses":[{"text":"Ruptured diverticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated appendix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13252,"text":"A 40-year-old female presents to the emergency department with severe epigastric pain. She is unable to sit straight and the pain decreases when she leans forward. She is febrile and tachycardic. Abdominal examination reveals severe tenderness in her epigastrium. A diagnosis of acute pancreatitis was made. Serum amylase and lipase levels were elevated. Ultrasound abdomen showed a swollen pancreas. Which of the following laboratory findings indicate a good prognosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Basit H, Ruan GJ, Mukherjee S. Ranson criteria. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 9, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482345/","responses":[{"text":"Elevated AST","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated hematocrit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated LDH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated blood glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated WBC","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13255,"text":"Which of the following is the definition of a wound?","explanation":"**Wound** refers to a **break in the continuation of tissue**.\r\n\r\nA wound can be caused by a variety of mechanisms, including sharp or blunt trauma, burns, chemicals, and more. The other answer choices do not define a wound.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 188.","responses":[{"text":"An ulcer is a type of a wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a break in the continuation of tissue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is caused by a sharp weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is caused by a blunt weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Force is an essential element in its causation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13263,"text":"Which of the following is not related to an abrasion?","explanation":"**Abrasions** are superficial injuries that only involve the outermost layers of the skin. Due to their superficial nature, abrasions generally **do not leave permanent scars**, though they might leave temporary marks.\r\n\r\nRadiator grill refers to the patterned abrasion that can occur if someone is hit by a car and comes into contact with the front grille. The distinct pattern of the grille can leave a mark on the skin resembling its design.\r\n\r\nSince abrasions can result from contact with various surfaces, materials from that surface (like fibers, dirt, or other particles) may become embedded in the abrasion, providing potential evidence in forensic investigations.\r\n\r\nAbrasion typically results due to friction of rough object against skin. Common examples include falling on a rough surface like asphalt or being dragged on the ground.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 189-190.","responses":[{"text":"Leaves scar mark","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Are superficial injuries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiator grill","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are caused by friction of rough object against skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contain trace evidence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13304,"text":"A worker employed in the soldering industry is found to have sideroblastic anemia. He was also found to have wrist and foot drop. He was diagnosed as being chronically exposed to an element at his workplace. What is the mechanism of action of this element?","explanation":"The clinical picture described is consistent with lead poisoning. Chronic exposure to lead, especially in industrial settings such as soldering, can lead to sideroblastic anemia and the neurological symptoms of wrist and foot drop.\r\n\r\nLead inhibits **ALA dehydratase** (also known as porphobilinogen synthase) and **ferrochelatase**. The inhibition of ALA dehydratase leads to the accumulation of aminolevulinic acid (ALA), which is neurotoxic and contributes to the neurological symptoms of lead poisoning.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 278-279.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibition of ALA synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of chelatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of amino levulinic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of ALA dehydratase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13306,"text":"What defines a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 191.","responses":[{"text":"The weapon used can be recognized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is caused by a blunt weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous tissue due to blunt trauma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It may help determine the time of affliction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It changes color with time","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13308,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding a migratory bruise?","explanation":"A **migratory bruise** refers to the phenomenon where a bruise or ecchymosis **appears away from the actual site of injury**, usually due to the movement of blood along tissue planes or gravitational force. This can be observed in certain injuries where the bleeding from the injury site travels to a dependent location due to the pull of gravity. For example, an injury around the eye (peri-orbital region) can lead to ecchymosis appearing over time in the submandibular region or even the neck.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 192.","responses":[{"text":"May appear away from the impact site","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"May appear immediately","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May appear during re-examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May not appear at all","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May appear within hours","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13310,"text":"A worker who glazes pottery presents to the clinic with the complaint of bluish-black lines at the junction of his gums and teeth. What is the causative agent of these lines?","explanation":"The bluish-black lines at the gum-tooth junction, often referred to as a \"lead line\" or \"Burton's line\", are caused by **lead deposition**. This is a classic symptom of chronic lead poisoning","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 501.","responses":[{"text":"Glazing paint deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead nitro-sulphide deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead sulphide deposition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphide deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead deposition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13311,"text":"Which of the following is  not true regarding a grinding laceration?","explanation":"A **grinding laceration** typically results from a heavy weight or force that crushes and avulses the skin from the underlying tissues. It is characterized by irregular, torn skin edges and is often associated with significant soft tissue damage and hemorrhage. While such lacerations can occur in road traffic accidents or due to heavy weights, they are not typically the result of a fall from height. A fall from height may result in other types of injuries, but a grinding laceration specifically is more indicative of a crushing force against the tissue.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 196.","responses":[{"text":"Occurs in road traffic accidents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accompanied by extreme extravasation of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May result from fall from height","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Caused by heavy weight with avulsion of skin from underlying tissues","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"May result in crush syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13312,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect for an incised wound?","explanation":"An **incised wound** is a cut that is longer than it is deep, usually resulting from a sharp-edged object such as a knife, razor, or glass.\r\n\r\nDue to the sharp nature of the weapon or object causing an incised wound, the **edges of the wound are usually clean** and straight, as opposed to the more ragged or irregular edges seen in lacerations or other wound types.\r\n\r\nWhile many incised wounds can be painful due to damage to the skin and underlying tissues, the level of pain experienced can vary depending on factors like the location of the wound, depth, individual pain tolerance, and whether or not any nerves were affected. For instance, wounds that are superficial or that do not involve many nerve endings might not be painful.\r\n\r\nIncised wounds can lead to significant blood loss because of their typically clean and straight nature, which does not encourage immediate blood clotting as might be seen with more jagged wounds.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Bleeds profusely","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A wound with clean edges","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is always caused by a sharp weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It Is always painful","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The maximum measurement of an incised wound is its length","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13347,"text":"A 60-year-old male presented to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain. On examination, his abdomen was soft and non-tender. His X-ray abdomen was done which shows peripheral bowel loops with haustra. What is this segment of the gastrointestinal tract called?","explanation":"The segment of the gastrointestinal tract that displays peripheral bowel loops with **haustra** is the **colon**. \r\n\r\nThe haustra are the small pouches caused by sacculation (sac formation) in the colon, which give it a segmented appearance. This feature distinguishes the colon from other parts of the intestines on radiographic images. The jejunum, ileum, and duodenum are parts of the small intestine and do not have haustra. The stomach also does not have haustra.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 468.","responses":[{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13349,"text":"A 40-year-old man presents to the clinic with yellow pigmentation of skin and sclera. Which of the following conditions is the most likely cause of this patient's obstructive jaundice?","explanation":"The most likely cause of obstructive jaundice in this patient is **cancer in the head of the pancreas**.\r\n\r\n**Obstructive jaundice** occurs when there's a blockage in the ducts that transport bile from the liver to the intestines. The head of the pancreas is anatomically close to the common bile duct. A tumor in this location can compress the duct and cause obstruction, leading to jaundice.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTumors in the body or tail of the pancreas are less likely to cause jaundice since they do not usually impinge upon the common bile duct.\r\n\r\nObstruction of the main pancreatic duct could lead to pancreatitis but not typically jaundice, as it does not obstruct the bile flow.\r\n\r\nAneurysm of the splenic artery or aorta would not typically cause jaundice.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 893.","responses":[{"text":"Obstruction of main pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aneurysm of splenic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cancer in the body of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aneurysm of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cancer in the head of pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13358,"text":"Which of the following hormones stimulates the secretion of gastric juice?","explanation":"The hormone that stimulates the secretion of gastric juice is **gastrin**. It is produced by G-cells in the stomach in response to the presence of proteins and other stimuli. It stimulates the gastric glands to secrete gastric juice, which contains hydrochloric acid and pepsinogen.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSomatostatin has an inhibitory effect on various processes, including the release of growth hormone and thyroid-stimulating hormone. In the stomach, somatostatin inhibits gastric acid secretion.\r\n\r\nGlucose-dependent insulinotropic hormone (GIP) is secreted by the small intestine in response to the ingestion of food and stimulates insulin release.\r\n\r\nSecretin is released from the small intestine in response to acidic chyme entering from the stomach. It stimulates bicarbonate secretion from the pancreas to neutralize the acid, rather than stimulating gastric juice secretion.\r\n\r\nCholecystokinin (CCK) stimulates gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion into the small intestine. It also slows down the emptying of the stomach.","reference":"Costanzo LS. Physiology. 6th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 344.","responses":[{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose-dependantinsulinotropic hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystokinin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13362,"text":"A 45-year-old male with peptic ulcer disease presents to the emergency department with an abrupt onset of severe epigastric pain for the past 1 hour. Abdominal examination raises suspicion for an acute surgical abdomen. Which of the following examination findings is not suggestive of perforation?","explanation":null,"reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1125, 1048.","responses":[{"text":"Perforation accounts for two-thirds of peptic ulcer-related deaths","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis may result from posterior perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tympanitic abdomen may indicate free air, confirmed by upright chest X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A reactive pleural effusion is frequently seen with gastric perforation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical peritonitis progresses to abdominal rigidity, bacterial peritonitis, and sepsis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13365,"text":"Which of the following is a disadvantage of the \"food frequency questionnaire\" method of obtaining food intake data?","explanation":"The \"food frequency questionnaire\" (FFQ) is a common method used in nutritional epidemiology to assess the long-term dietary intake of individuals. Like all dietary assessment tools, the FFQ has its advantages and limitations. One of its primary limitations is the potential for both **underestimation or overestimation** of food and nutrient intake. This is because the FFQ relies on the memory and perception of the respondent to recall their typical eating habits over a longer period, and it can be influenced by issues like portion size estimation, forgetfulness about certain foods, or even biases due to perceived social desirability.","reference":"Munoz N, Bernstein M, eds. Nutrition Assessment: Clinical and Research Applications. 1st ed. Jones \u0026 Barlett Learning; 2019: 191.","responses":[{"text":"Influenced by food choices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ignore long-term changes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inaccurate nutrient intake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seasonal variability affects result","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Underestimation or overestimation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13369,"text":"During the evaluation of changes in a subject's body weight, what does a 94% usual body weight (UBW) represent?","explanation":"In the context of evaluating nutritional status, a person's percentage of usual body weight (UBW) can provide insight into their **risk of malnutrition**. Typically, the following classification is adopted:\r\n\r\n- 85% or less of UBW: Severe nutritional risk\r\n- 86% to 90% of UBW: Moderate nutritional risk\r\n- 91% to 95% of UBW: Mild nutritional risk\r\n- More than 95% of UBW: No nutritional risk\r\n\r\nGiven that the subject's body weight is 94% of their UBW, this would represent **mild nutritional risk**.","reference":"Munoz N, Bernstein M, eds. Nutrition Assessment: Clinical and Research Applications. 1st ed. Jones \u0026 Barlett Learning; 2019: 231.","responses":[{"text":"Mild nutritional risk","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Borderline nutritional risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Moderate nutritional risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No nutritional risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe nutritional risk","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13371,"text":"During a nutritional care plan, which of the following nutritional aspects is a \"PES statement\" used to present?","explanation":"A \"PES statement\" is used to present the **diagnosis** in a nutritional care plan. \r\n\r\nThe PES stands for:\r\n- **P**roblem (the nutrition diagnosis itself)\r\n- **E**tiology (the cause or contributing risk factors)\r\n- **S**igns/Symptoms (evidence that the problem exists)","reference":"Munoz N, Bernstein M, eds. Nutrition Assessment: Clinical and Research Applications. 1st ed. Jones \u0026 Barlett Learning; 2019: 14.","responses":[{"text":"Intervention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Evaluation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diagnosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Assessment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Planning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13372,"text":"A 50-year-old male is admitted to the intensive care unit with severe burns. He weighs 80 kg and has a height of 177 cm. What will be the injury factor that will be used in Long's formula to calculate his daily energy requirement?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Medical Nutrition Therapy, Sub-topic: Calories and Energy.","responses":[{"text":"2.5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.35","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2.1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1.2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13373,"text":"Which of the following is an indicator of a nutritionally at-risk adult?","explanation":"**Involuntary weight loss of ≥ 5%** in a month is an indicator of a nutritionally at-risk adult.\r\n\r\nRapid, involuntary weight loss can be a sign of underlying medical issues or malnutrition. It is essential to investigate the cause, as it might indicate a serious health condition, reduced ability to heal and recover, and increased risk of morbidity and mortality. In the context of assessing nutritional risk, factors like sudden weight changes, especially when unintended, play a crucial role.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Medical Nutrition Therapy, Sub-topic: Calories and Energy.","responses":[{"text":"Involuntary weight loss of ≥ 5% in a month","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental pollution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Voluntary weight gain of 6.5 kg in a month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seasonal flu","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index less than 25 kg/m²","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13375,"text":"Which of the following organs synthesizes albumin?","explanation":"The liver plays a crucial role in the synthesis of many proteins that circulate in the bloodstream, one of which is albumin. **Albumin** is the most abundant protein in human blood plasma. It serves several essential functions, including regulation of oncotic pressure, transport, and as a nutrient source.\r\n\r\nWhen the liver is damaged or diseased, such as in cirrhosis or hepatitis, its ability to produce albumin can be compromised. A decrease in serum albumin levels can be indicative of liver dysfunction, among other possible causes. Thus, measuring albumin levels can be a valuable tool in assessing liver function and overall nutritional status.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 178.","responses":[{"text":"Brain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13378,"text":"A country in central Africa has high mortality and a high birth rate. The experts wish to classify the country's stage of demographic transition. Which of the following correctly captures the stage of the given country?","explanation":"The demographic transition model describes the progression of countries as they move from high birth and death rates to low birth and death rates through time due to development. The stages of the demographic transition model are as follows:\r\n\r\n**Stage 1 (pre-transitional):** Both high birth and death rates. Population growth is slow and fluctuating. Most societies were in this stage until the late 18th century.\r\n**Stage 2 (early transitional):** Death rates decline due to improvements in food supply and sanitation, leading to population growth. Birth rates remain high.\r\n**Stage 3 (mid-transitional):** Birth rates start to decline due to improved economic conditions, better education, and access to contraception. Population growth starts to moderate.\r\n**Stage 4 (late transitional):** Both birth and death rates are low, balancing each other out. Population growth is minimal or even becomes negative.\r\n**Stage 5 (post-transitional):** Birth rates fall even further, below replacement level, leading to a declining population, though death rates might remain low.\r\n\r\nGiven the described characteristics of the country in central Africa with high mortality and a high birth rate, it would be classified as being in **stage 1 (pre-transitional)** of the demographic transition.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Demography, Sub-topic: Demographic Transition: Stages.","responses":[{"text":"Stage 5 (post-transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 2 (early transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 1 (pre-transitional)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 3 (mid-transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 4 (late transitional)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13381,"text":"A country has a growth rate (r) of 3%. Experts want to make policies for better planning and administration. For this purpose, they want to calculate the number of years needed for the population to double, based on the current growth rate. Which of the following options captures the correct population doubling time of the country, based on the given information?","explanation":"To estimate the doubling time for a population given a constant growth rate, we can use the rule of 70 (also known as the Rule of 70 Doubling Time formula):\r\n\r\nDoubling time (T)= 70/Growth rate (r)\r\n\r\nSo, the population doubling time for the country, based on a growth rate of 3%, is approximately **23.3 years**.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Demography, Sub-topic: Demographic Transition: Stages.","responses":[{"text":"100 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"70 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"35 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"140 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"23.3 years","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13382,"text":"What does natality refer to?","explanation":"Natality, in the context of population ecology, refers to the **birth rate of a population**. Specifically, it denotes the number of live births in a given population during a specified time interval, often expressed per 1,000 individuals per year. Natality is a crucial factor in determining the growth rate of a population. Along with mortality (death rate), immigration (number of individuals entering the habitat), and emigration (number of individuals leaving the habitat), natality helps in understanding population dynamics and predicting future population sizes.","reference":"Bloom-Feshbach K, Simonsen L, Viboud C, et al. Natality decline and miscarriages associated with the 1918 influenza pandemic: the scandinavian and united states experiences. The Journal of Infectious Diseases. Published October 15, 2011. Accessed December 11, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3203382/","responses":[{"text":"Number of individuals leaving the habitat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Death rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ratio of men and women","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Number of individuals entering the habitat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Birth rate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13459,"text":"A 6-year-old girl is brought to the clinic with a history of jaundice for the last 10 days. She has had nausea and vomiting with decreased oral intake for the past 15 days. She has also had an altered state of consciousness for the past 2 days. On examination, she has a Glasgow coma scale score of 10/15 with severe jaundice. Her liver is tender and palpable 2.5 cm below the costal margin. Laboratory testing shows hypoglycemia with deranged liver function test values and a PT-INR \u003e 3.0. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with a short duration of jaundice (10 days), altered consciousness, a palpable tender liver, and markedly deranged liver function tests, including a significantly prolonged PT-INR, is indicative of **acute liver failure**. The altered state of consciousness and the low Glasgow coma scale score suggest **hepatic encephalopathy**, which can be a complication of acute liver failure. \r\n\r\nWhile hepatic encephalopathy can also occur in chronic liver disease and acute on chronic liver disease, the presentation is acute in nature, and there is no mention of prior liver-related symptoms or issues, which makes an acute process more likely.\r\n\r\nCerebral malaria typically presents with fever and neurological symptoms but does not cause jaundice and liver tenderness as primary symptoms. Hepatic encephalitis is not a standard clinical term; encephalitis refers to inflammation of the brain, which is distinct from hepatic encephalopathy, a neuropsychiatric syndrome resulting from liver dysfunction.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 872-875.","responses":[{"text":"Cerebral malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute liver failure with hepatic encephalopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute on chronic liver disease with hepatic encephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13464,"text":"What are the diagnostic criteria for acute liver failure?","explanation":"The diagnostic criteria for **acute liver failure** include:\r\n\r\n- Symptoms for a duration of less than **8 weeks**.\r\n- An elevated prothrombin time (**PT-INR \u003e 1.5**), which indicates impaired liver function.\r\n- The presence of **hepatic encephalopathy**, a neuropsychiatric manifestation of liver dysfunction.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Pediatrics, Topic: Viral Hepatitis, Acute Hepatic Failure, Storage and Metabolic Disorders, Sub-topic: Acute Hepatic Failure.","responses":[{"text":"Symptoms \u003e 6 weeks with hepatic encephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms \u003c 8 weeks with PT-INR \u003e 1.5 and hepatic encephalopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms \u003e 6 weeks with PT-INR \u003e 1.5 and hepatic encephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms \u003c 8 weeks with normal PT-INR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms \u003c 6 weeks with PT-INR \u003e 1.5 and hepatic encephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13465,"text":"Which of the following is not a precipitating risk factor for hepatitis-induced encephalopathy?","explanation":"**Neoplasm** is not a precipitating risk factor for **hepatitis-induced (or hepatic) encephalopathy**.\r\n\r\nHepatic encephalopathy is a neuropsychiatric syndrome caused by liver dysfunction. Precipitating factors can worsen a pre-existing liver condition, leading to an increased risk of encephalopathy. Factors such as pneumonia (due to increased catabolism or direct bacterial toxins), dietary protein load (resulting in increased ammonia production), paracentesis (especially if performed without albumin replacement, leading to rapid shifts in plasma osmolality), and dehydration (which can impair renal function and result in decreased clearance of ammonia) can precipitate hepatic encephalopathy in a patient with liver disease. However, neoplasms, by themselves, are not direct precipitating factors for hepatic encephalopathy.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 878.","responses":[{"text":"Dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paracentesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dietary protein load","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neoplasm","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13467,"text":"What is the prime treatment of ascites secondary to portal hypertension?","explanation":"The prime treatment for ascites secondary to portal hypertension includes **sodium restriction** and **diuretics**. Sodium restriction is essential because excessive sodium intake can worsen fluid retention. Diuretics help to increase sodium and water excretion, further reducing the fluid volume in the body. Commonly used diuretics in this context include spironolactone (an aldosterone antagonist) and furosemide (a loop diuretic).\r\n\r\nWhile beta-blockers can be used to reduce portal hypertension and decrease the risk of variceal bleeding, they are not the primary treatment for ascites. \r\n\r\nTherapeutic paracentesis is a procedure used to remove large volumes of ascitic fluid and is typically reserved for patients with tense or refractory ascites. It provides symptomatic relief but is not the primary long-term management strategy. \r\n\r\nFluid restriction may be necessary in cases of hyponatremia. \r\n\r\nAntibiotics are not a first-line treatment for ascites unless there's evidence of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP).","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 876.","responses":[{"text":"Beta-blockers, diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium restriction, diuretics","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diuretics, nitrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic paracentesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluid restriction, beta-blockers, anitbiotics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13469,"text":"A young male presents to the emergency department with the complaint of blood in vomiting and an altered level of consciousness since last night. Attendants describe that he had four bouts of large-volume, black-colored vomiting after which he became drowsy. On examination, his blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, pulse is 112 beats per minute, he is drowsy and anemic, and has bipedal edema and clubbing. His abdomen is non-tender with an enlarged spleen and ascites. What is the most likely cause of his bleeding?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with an altered level of consciousness after vomiting blood, along with physical findings like anemia, ascites, splenomegaly, bipedal edema, and clubbing, are suggestive of **chronic liver disease with portal hypertension**. \r\n\r\nOne of the most serious complications of portal hypertension is the development of **esophageal varices**, which are abnormally dilated blood vessels in the esophagus. These varices are prone to rupture and can cause massive, life-threatening bleeding. The presence of large-volume, black-colored vomit (hematemesis with the blood often appearing as \"coffee grounds\") is consistent with bleeding from esophageal varices.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 881-882.","responses":[{"text":"Peptic ulcer disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory Weiss syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erosive gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeding esophageal varices","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13472,"text":"A middle-aged female presents to the outpatient department with the complaint of gradual distention of the abdomen for the past 4 months and pedal edema for 3 weeks. There is no history of nocturia or periorbital puffiness. Her abdomen is distended and her spleen is palpable three fingers below the costal margin. Shifting dullness is also positive. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms of gradual abdominal distention (likely due to ascites) over months, combined with pedal edema and splenomegaly, are characteristic findings in **chronic liver disease**. The presence of **shifting dullness** on examination is indicative of free fluid in the abdomen (ascites), a common manifestation of liver disease, particularly when cirrhosis or significant liver dysfunction is present. The **splenomegaly** may be a result of portal hypertension, another complication of chronic liver disease.\r\n\r\nWhile the other conditions can also present with abdominal distention or pedal edema, the combination of these signs with the specific finding of splenomegaly and shifting dullness makes chronic liver disease the most likely diagnosis in this patient.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 828-830.","responses":[{"text":"Malabsorption syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic liver disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive cardiac failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13476,"text":"In the normal plain X-ray abdomen, the gas shadow in the central part of the abdomen indicates which anatomical segment of the gastrointestinal tract?","explanation":"In a normal plain X-ray of the abdomen, the gas shadow seen in the central part of the abdomen typically corresponds to the small intestines, particularly the **jejunum and ileum**. \r\n\r\nThe jejunum and ileum are segments of the small intestine, with the jejunum lying proximal to the ileum. On a plain X-ray, the gas-filled loops of the small intestine often appear centrally, while the gas-filled colon generally frames the periphery of the abdomen. The distribution of gas can vary based on multiple factors, but in general, the central gas shadows on a plain abdominal X-ray often represent the jejunum and ileum.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Radiology, Topic: Normal and Abnormal GI Patterns on X-ray Abdomen, Sub-topic: Bowel Gas Pattern.","responses":[{"text":"Colon and jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum and stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum and colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach and ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum and jejunum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15538,"text":"A patient starts having diarrhea after taking antibiotics during his hospital stay. Which organism is most likely involved?","explanation":"The most likely organism involved in a patient who develops diarrhea after taking antibiotics during a hospital stay is:\r\n***Clostridium difficile***, commonly referred to as C. diff, is a bacterium that can cause symptoms ranging from diarrhea to life-threatening inflammation of the colon. It is often associated with antibiotic use, particularly in **hospitalized patients**, as antibiotics can disrupt the normal gut flora, allowing for C. difficile overgrowth and resulting in disease. This condition is often referred to as ***Clostridium difficile***-**associated diarrhea (CDAD)** or ***C. difficile*** **infection (CDI)**. The management of the condition may involve discontinuation of the offending antibiotic and initiation of specific antibiotic therapy against C. difficile.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 136.","responses":[{"text":"Clostridium botulinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium tetani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15620,"text":"A man presents to the hospital with an altered level of consciousness two hours after falling in the washroom. He has pinpoint pupils with a pulse of 78 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 180/120 mmHg, and a fever of 107°F despite antipyretics. Sponging is also of no use. What is the most likely cause of fever?","explanation":"The clinical picture presented, especially with an altered level of consciousness following a fall, pinpoint pupils, lack of response to antipyretics, and extremely high fever, strongly suggests a central nervous system pathology. A **pontine hemorrhage** (specifically, a bleed in the pons region of the brainstem) is the most consistent with these findings. \r\n\r\nA pontine hemorrhage can directly affect the temperature-regulating centers of the brain, leading to hyperthermia. The pons is also responsible for parasympathetic output, which explains the pinpoint pupils (due to unopposed parasympathetic activity). The hypertension and bradycardia can be explained by the Cushing reflex in response to increased intracranial pressure from the hemorrhage.","reference":"Amorim, Robson Luis Oliveira de, et al. “Current Clinical Approach to Patients with Disorders of Consciousness.” Revista Da Associação Médica Brasileira, vol. 62, July 2016, pp. 377–84. SciELO, https://doi.org/10.1590/1806-9282.62.04.377.","responses":[{"text":"Cerebral malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pontine hemorrhage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16730,"text":"A 70-year-old man was brought to the hospital due to his cardiac conditions. Upon history, it was found that he has no physical activity in his daily schedule and oil is often reused in home-cooked food for the cooking. After a detailed examination, the doctor suggested a change in his sedentary lifestyle and dietary habits. The change is necessary to produce which of the following outcomes?","explanation":"The aim of suggesting changes in a sedentary lifestyle and avoiding the reuse of cooking oil is to benefit the cardiovascular health of the patient. Reusing cooking oil can lead to the **formation of peroxidants**, which are harmful substances that can contribute to oxidative stress in the body. Oxidative stress can damage cells, proteins, and DNA, and it plays a role in aging and the development of many conditions including cardiovascular diseases.\r\n\r\nMoreover, a sedentary lifestyle can negatively affect lipid profiles, including increasing levels of low-density lipoproteins (LDL), which are considered \"bad\" cholesterol. Elevated LDL levels can contribute to atherosclerosis and other cardiovascular diseases.","reference":"Prabhu HR. Lipid peroxidation in culinary oils subjected to thermal stress. Indian Journal of Clinical Biochemistry. Published August 2000. Accessed July 7, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3453543/","responses":[{"text":"To increase non radicals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To increase low density lipoproteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To decrease peroxidants","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"To decrease high density lipoproteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To increase free radicals in diet","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16738,"text":"What is true about the oxidative rancidification of oils?","explanation":"**Oxidative rancidification** is a process in which unsaturated fats or oils are oxidized, typically due to the action of oxygen in air. It leads to the formation of off-flavors and off-odors in the oil or fat.\r\n\r\nDuring oxidative rancidification, the double bonds of an unsaturated fatty acid can be cleaved, leading to the formation of aldehydes, ketones, and other compounds, which contribute to the unpleasant smell and taste of rancid oil.","reference":"Velasco J, Dobarganes C, Márquez-Ruiz G, Skibsted LH, Risbo J, Andersen ML. 1 - Oxidative rancidity in foods and food quality. Chemical Deterioration and Physical Instability of Food and Beverages. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/B9781845694951500010","responses":[{"text":"Rancid oil has decreased aldehydes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rancid oil has decreased ketones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen reacts with the unsaturated fatty acids","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rancid oil has increased omega fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbondioxide reacts with the saturated fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16739,"text":"A man with chronic liver failure due to hepatitis B was brought to the hospital. His imaging reports show regenerative parenchymal nodules with fibrous bands and variable degrees of vascular shunting. Which of the following best describes the mentioned condition?","explanation":"**Cirrhosis** is a late-stage liver disease in which healthy liver tissue is replaced with scar tissue and the liver is permanently damaged. Imaging shows **regenerative parenchymal nodules** with **fibrous bands** and variable degrees of vascular shunting, The scar tissue prevents the liver from working properly. This condition can be caused by various factors, including long-standing hepatitis B infection, as mentioned in the scenario.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 827.","responses":[{"text":"Non alcoholic fatty liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Portal hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol intoxication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16742,"text":"A 35-year-old female patient reports having epigastric abdominal pain for the last 7 months and has also lost 10 kg weight during this time. She is currently taking proton pump inhibitors (PPI) for her Barrett esophagus. She has recently been experiencing dysphagia and is a heavy smoker with no history of steroids or NSAIDs. What she is at risk of developing?","explanation":"This woman's long-standing epigastric pain, significant weight loss, existing diagnosis of Barrett's esophagus, the recent onset of dysphagia, and history of heavy smoking are suggestive of underlying **malignancy**.\r\n\r\n**Barrett esophagus** is a known risk factor for esophageal adenocarcinoma. The new symptoms of dysphagia (difficulty swallowing) and significant weight loss further raise concerns about the potential development of malignancy. Additionally, smoking is a well-known risk factor for various cancers, including those of the esophagus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 758.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal webs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barrett esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indigestion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignancy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer perforation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16773,"text":"A 9-year-old child presents with a prolonged history of abdominal discomfort, bloating, constipation, weight loss, and anemia. Serological examination shows positivity for anti-endomysial antibodies. An endoscopic biopsy of the jejunum shows villous atrophy. Which of the following should be avoided?","explanation":"The child's symptoms of abdominal discomfort, bloating, constipation, weight loss, anemia, as well as the positive serological test for anti-endomysial antibodies and a biopsy showing villous atrophy, all point towards a diagnosis of **celiac disease**. \r\n\r\nCeliac disease is an autoimmune condition where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. Gluten is a protein found in certain grains, particularly wheat, barley, and rye.\r\n\r\n**Bread** is the most relevant item that should be avoided, as it typically contains wheat, a primary source of gluten.\r\n\r\nThe other substances, such as **mucilage**, **pectin**, **cellulose**, and **lignin**, do not contain gluten.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 782.","responses":[{"text":"Cellulose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bread","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lignin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucilage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16776,"text":"Which of the following is the effect of misoprostol on the gastrointestinal tract?","explanation":"**Misoprostol** is a synthetic prostaglandin E1 analog. It exerts its protective effects on the gastric mucosa by **increasing bicarbonate and mucus secretion**, thus enhancing the mucosal barrier. It also inhibits gastric acid secretion. This makes it useful in the prevention of gastric ulcers in patients taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), which can cause mucosal damage and ulceration.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 510.","responses":[{"text":"Increase in gastric acid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase B12  absorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in lipid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protection of mucosal lining","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocking H2 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16777,"text":"A patient with chronic liver disease and cirrhosis develops thrombocytopenia due to which of the following reasons mainly?","explanation":"In a patient with chronic liver disease, cirrhosis can lead to **portal hypertension**. This, in turn, causes the spleen to enlarge (splenomegaly) as blood flow through the liver becomes obstructed and gets rerouted to the spleen. An enlarged spleen (due to **hypersplenism**) can sequester or trap more platelets than usual, leading to a reduction of platelets in the circulation, thus causing **thrombocytopenia**.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 830.","responses":[{"text":"Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubinemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersplenism","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16778,"text":"A 20-year-old woman consults her physician with recurrent abdominal pain, bloating, and discomfort for the last 6 months. She also complains of altered bowel habits, predominantly diarrhea. Her abdominal pain improves after passing stool. There is no history of fever and weight loss. Physical examination is unremarkable. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)** is a functional gastrointestinal disorder characterized by **recurrent abdominal pain** or discomfort, often associated with changes in bowel habits (either diarrhea, constipation, or both). The pain typically improves after passing stool. There are no structural abnormalities in the intestines, and physical examination is typically unremarkable. The absence of systemic symptoms like fever and weight loss also distinguishes IBS from inflammatory conditions like ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 796.","responses":[{"text":"Protein-losing enteropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyrotoxicosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16790,"text":"A 52-year-old female presented to the emergency department with jaundice, increased heart rate nausea, sweating, and progressive right upper quadrant pain. She had a history of pale stools and dark-colored urine. Ultrasound showed intracanalicular cholestasis and dilated bile canaliculi but there were no signs of necrosis, fibrosis, or iron deposition. What could be the cause of her clinical picture?","explanation":"The patient's clinical presentation is suggestive of an obstruction in the biliary system. The presence of jaundice, pale stools, and dark-colored urine indicates an obstructive pathology. The ultrasound findings of intracanalicular cholestasis and dilated bile canaliculi further support this. The most common cause of biliary obstruction in adults is **gallstones obstructing the cystic ducts.** This leads to cholestasis (reduced bile flow) and subsequent symptoms of obstruction. The patient's symptoms and the ultrasound findings are consistent with this diagnosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 878.","responses":[{"text":"Hemochromatosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Centrilobular necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gallstones obstructing the cystic ducts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma of gall bladder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16956,"text":"A 50-year-old male presented to the outpatient department with a complaint of right upper quadrant pain along with jaundice, dark urine, and pale stools. Radiographic studies of the gallbladder showed dilated segments alternating with fibrotic areas of intra and extra-hepatic ducts. What would be the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis is **primary sclerosing cholangitis**. Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is a chronic liver disease characterized by **inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts**, leading to the formation of **strictures**. These strictures can cause the alternating appearance of dilation and fibrosis. PSC often presents with right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, dark urine, and pale stools due to obstruction of the bile ducts.\r\n\r\n\r\nBiliary atresia is a congenital condition in which the bile ducts are absent or have become obstructed, leading to the buildup of bile in the liver. This condition would typically present early in life.\r\n\r\nPrimary hepatolithiasis refers to the formation of stones in the intrahepatic bile ducts, primarily seen in Asian countries. While it can cause symptoms like jaundice, the radiographic findings would not typically show the \"beading\" appearance described.\r\n\r\nCholelithiasis refers to the formation of gallstones within the gallbladder. While this can cause right upper quadrant pain and even jaundice if a stone obstructs the common bile duct, the radiographic findings would likely show stones in the gallbladder rather than the described changes in the intra and extra-hepatic ducts.\r\n\r\nCholedochal cysts are congenital conditions characterized by cystic dilations of the bile ducts. They can cause jaundice and right upper quadrant pain, but the radiographic findings would typically show a cystic dilation rather than the beaded appearance of the bile ducts described for PSC.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 859.","responses":[{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliary atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary hepatolithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choledochal cysts","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17140,"text":"A patient presented to the outpatient department with a history of liver enlargement, pain, hyperbilirubinemia, and ascites. Imaging showed multiple venous thrombi in hepatic veins. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for a patient with liver enlargement, pain, hyperbilirubinemia, ascites, and the presence of multiple venous thrombi in hepatic veins is **Budd-Chiari syndrome**. Budd-Chiari syndrome is a rare disorder characterized by **obstruction of the hepatic veins**, which transport blood from the liver to the inferior vena cava. This obstruction can lead to liver enlargement, pain, and other associated symptoms.\r\n\r\n\r\n- Primary biliary cirrhosis (now more commonly referred to as primary biliary cholangitis) is a chronic disease where the small bile ducts in the liver become inflamed and damaged and are ultimately destroyed. This can lead to a buildup of bile in the liver, causing scarring (cirrhosis). Its clinical picture might include jaundice and ascites, but it would not typically present with hepatic vein thrombi.\r\n\r\nCholelithiasis refers to the formation of gallstones within the gallbladder. While it can cause right upper quadrant pain and jaundice if a stone obstructs the common bile duct, it would not be associated with hepatic vein thrombi.\r\n\r\nPrimary sclerosing cholangitis is a chronic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts. It is not typically associated with hepatic vein thrombi but can show a beaded appearance on imaging due to strictures in the bile ducts.\r\n\r\nFibro-polycystic disease refers to a group of hereditary diseases that can affect the liver, such as polycystic liver disease. They might present with liver enlargement, but the characteristic finding would be cysts in the liver rather than hepatic vein thrombi.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 863.","responses":[{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibro-polycystic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Budd-Chiari syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary biliary cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17343,"text":"What is the data recording events in the population such as death, birth, social and economic status termed as?","explanation":"The data recording events in the population such as death, birth, social, and economic status is termed as **vital registration**.\r\n\r\n---\r\nA population pyramid is a graphical representation that shows the distribution of various age groups in a population. It typically illustrates the age and sex structure of a country's population.\r\n\r\nA population census is a complete count of a population, and it typically includes detailed information about individuals, such as their age, sex, occupation, and relationship to the head of the household.\r\n\r\nA health registry is a system of recording and maintaining specific information about the health status of individuals, usually focusing on specific diseases or conditions.\r\n\r\nCommunity medicine is a branch of medicine that is concerned with the health of the members of a community, region, or nation as opposed to individual health. It focuses on preventive medicine and public health practices.","reference":"CRVS. “What Are Civil Registration and Vital Statistics (CRVS) Systems?” World Health Organization - Regional Office for the Eastern Mediterranean, http://www.emro.who.int/civil-registration-statistics/about/what-are-civil-registration-and-vital-statistics-crvs-systems.html. Accessed 25 July 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Community medicine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population pyramid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population census","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Health registry","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital registration","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":17369,"text":"Which hormone is associated with increased appetite, especially during fasting and overeating in obese patients?","explanation":"The hormone associated with increased appetite, especially during fasting and overeating in obese patients, is **ghrelin**.\r\n\r\nLeptin is produced by fat cells and signals to the brain when you have enough fat stored. It suppresses appetite and increases energy expenditure. Obese individuals often have high levels of leptin, but their brains become resistant to it, which means they don't feel satiated and continue to eat.\r\n\r\nSecretin is a hormone released by the small intestine that stimulates the pancreas to release bicarbonate-rich pancreatic juice, which neutralizes the acidity of chyme entering the intestine. It doesn't directly influence appetite.\r\n\r\nGastrin is a hormone that stimulates the secretion of gastric acid (hydrochloric acid) by the parietal cells of the stomach and aids in gastric motility. It's mainly triggered by the presence of protein in the stomach.\r\n\r\nInsulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that allows cells to take in glucose from the bloodstream and use it for energy. It plays a role in regulating blood sugar levels and has a more indirect effect on hunger and appetite, with increased levels after meals leading to satiety.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 446.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghrelin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leptin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17371,"text":"Which of the following is the side effect of magnesium hydroxide on the gut?","explanation":"**Magnesium hydroxide** is commonly used as an antacid and a laxative. When consumed, it works by drawing water into the intestines from the surrounding tissues. This increase in water content softens and expands the stool, leading to an acceleration of intestinal motility. The result is more frequent bowel movements and a softening of the stool, which is why it is effective as a laxative. However, if taken in excessive amounts or for prolonged periods without adequate hydration, this effect can lead to **diarrhea**.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Gastric irritation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Constipation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17373,"text":"Which of the following is a convenient treatment option for the HCV genotype-1?","explanation":"**Sofosbuvir + velpatasvir** is a direct-acting antiviral regimen that is approved for treating all genotypes of HCV, including genotype 1. It is typically taken once daily for 12 weeks and has a high cure rate with a favorable side effect profile.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSofosbuvir + ribavirin - this combination has been used for some genotypes of HCV, but the addition of ribavirin might be needed for certain patients or genotypes and can introduce additional side effects.\r\n\r\nPegylated interferon has more side effects compared to the newer antiviral agents and is less commonly used in current HCV treatment regimens, especially when better-tolerated options like sofosbuvir and velpatasvir are available.\r\n\r\nOn its own, ribavirin is not a primary treatment for HCV. It is often combined with other antiviral agents but can cause significant side effects, including hemolytic anemia.","reference":"Karen Whalen, et al. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed., Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2019: 440.","responses":[{"text":"Sofosbuvir + velpatasvir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribavirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sofosbuvir + pegylated interferon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sofosbuvir + ribavirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sofosbuvir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17605,"text":"What is the role of carbenoxolone in treating ulcers?","explanation":"**Carbenoxolone** is used in the treatment of ulcers because it increases the production of mucus. The mucus plays a **protective role** in the stomach, forming a barrier that shields the stomach lining from the **corrosive effects of gastric acid**. Carbenoxolone is derived from the licorice root and has been used to promote the healing of gastric and duodenal ulcers by enhancing the mucosal barrier.\r\n\r\n\r\nIncreasing gastric acid production would be counterproductive in the management of ulcers, as excess acid can erode the protective lining of the stomach, leading to ulceration.\r\n\r\nSecretin primarily functions to stimulate the pancreas to release a fluid that neutralizes stomach acid, aiding in the digestion of food as it enters the small intestine. Increasing its production does not directly heal ulcers.\r\n\r\nIncreasing gastric cell turnover might theoretically help in the rapid healing of ulcers, but carbenoxolone does not have this effect.\r\n\r\nIncreasing gastric emptying would speed up the movement of food from the stomach to the small intestine. This does not directly aid in ulcer healing and is not an effect of carbenoxolone.","reference":"Pinder RM, Brogden RN, Sawyer PR, Speight TM, Spencer R, Avery GS. Carbenoxolone: a review of its pharmacological properties and therapeutic efficacy in peptic ulcer disease. Drugs. Published 1976. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/780088","responses":[{"text":"Increases secretin production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases gastric acid production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases production of mucus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases gastric emptying","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases gastric cells turnover","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17606,"text":"A child presented to the clinic with complaints of weight loss, chronic diarrhea typically triggered after eating wheat bread, nausea, and itchy rashes/blisters on the extensor surfaces of the body. Which of the following is the clinical diagnosis if the child appears anemic on examination?","explanation":"**Celiac disease** is the most likely clinical diagnosis for the child presenting with **weight loss, chronic diarrhea** triggered after eating wheat bread, nausea, **itchy rashes or blisters on the extensor surfaces of the body**, and appearing anemic on examination.\r\n\r\n**Celiac disease** is an autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten, found in wheat, barley, and rye, leads to damage in the small intestine. The symptoms can vary greatly, but gastrointestinal symptoms and dermatitis herpetiformis (itchy rashes) are common. Prolonged exposure to gluten in individuals with celiac disease can lead to malabsorption of nutrients, which can cause weight loss and anemia.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nLactase deficiency, commonly known as lactose intolerance, causes gastrointestinal symptoms like bloating, diarrhea, and gas after the consumption of lactose-containing products like milk. It does not cause rashes or anemia directly from the condition itself.\r\n\r\nSalmonella infection typically presents with symptoms of diarrhea, fever, and abdominal cramps. While it can lead to weight loss if chronic, it does not have a specific trigger like wheat bread, nor does it cause rashes on the extensor surfaces.\r\n\r\nAppendicitis is an inflammation of the appendix and usually presents acutely with pain starting around the navel and then moving to the lower right abdomen, nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite. It does not cause chronic diarrhea or rashes.\r\n\r\nTyphoid fever, caused by the *Salmonella typhi* bacteria, can lead to high fever, headache, abdominal pain, and constipation or diarrhea.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 782.","responses":[{"text":"Salmonella infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactase defeciency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17607,"text":"A 2-month-old child presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of watery frothy diarrhea and abdominal distention after milk ingestion. The child was exclusively breastfed, and stool volume was less than 200 mg/24 hours. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for a 2-month-old child presenting with watery, frothy diarrhea and abdominal distension after milk ingestion, especially when the child is exclusively breastfed, is **lactose intolerance**. \r\n\r\nLactose intolerance in infants, also known as congenital lactase deficiency, is a rare inherited disorder where the small intestine produces low levels of lactase, an enzyme that digests lactose. Lactose is a sugar found in milk and milk products, including breast milk. When lactose is not properly digested, it can lead to symptoms like diarrhea, gas, bloating, and abdominal pain. In exclusively breastfed babies, the introduction of lactose from the mother's milk can trigger the symptoms.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCeliac disease is an autoimmune disorder triggered by gluten ingestion in genetically predisposed individuals. While it can cause gastrointestinal symptoms, it usually does not manifest at such an early age, and the trigger is gluten, not lactose.\r\n\r\nGiardiasis is an intestinal infection caused by the Giardia parasite. It can lead to watery diarrhea, stomach cramps, and other gastrointestinal symptoms.\r\n\r\nWhile viral infections can cause diarrhea in infants, the specific association of symptoms with milk ingestion makes a general viral infection less likely as the primary cause.\r\n\r\nCow milk protein allergy is an allergic reaction to the protein in cow milk. However, since the baby is exclusively breastfed and has not been introduced to cow milk or cow milk-based formulas, this option is less likely.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 784.","responses":[{"text":"Viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactose intolerance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cow milk protein allergy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17610,"text":"A child from a consanguineous marriage is brought to the outpatient department with the complaint of pneumonia and other recurrent respiratory tract infections and fatty stools. What could be the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Cystic fibrosis** is the most likely diagnosis for a child with recurrent respiratory tract infections, pneumonia, and fatty stools (steatorrhea), especially in the context of consanguineous marriage (which increases the risk of autosomal recessive diseases).\r\n\r\n\r\n**Cystic fibrosis** is an autosomal recessive genetic disorder that affects the lungs, pancreas, and other organs. It results in thick mucus production, which can lead to respiratory and digestive problems. Respiratory manifestations include **chronic cough, recurrent respiratory infections**, and **pneumonia**. Digestive manifestations arise due to the malfunctioning of the pancreas, leading to malabsorption of fats and resulting in **fatty stools**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Phenylketonuria** is an inherited metabolic disorder in which individuals lack an enzyme to metabolize phenylalanine to tyrosine, leading to a buildup of phenylalanine in the body. Symptoms mainly revolve around neurologic issues like intellectual disability, seizures, and a musty body odor. It does not present with respiratory infections and fatty stools.\r\n\r\n**Jaundice** refers to the yellowing of the skin and eyes due to elevated levels of bilirubin in the blood. While it can be a symptom of many diseases, on its own, it does not explain the child's respiratory and gastrointestinal symptoms.\r\n\r\n**Celiac disease** is an autoimmune disorder triggered by gluten ingestion in genetically predisposed individuals. It leads to inflammation and damage in the small intestine, causing malabsorption and resulting in symptoms like diarrhea, weight loss, and fatty stools. While it can explain the fatty stools, it does not typically result in recurrent respiratory infections.\r\n\r\n**Lactose insufficiency** refers to a deficiency in lactase, the enzyme responsible for breaking down lactose. It can lead to bloating, diarrhea, and abdominal pain after consuming lactose-containing products but does not cause recurrent respiratory infections.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 466.","responses":[{"text":"Lactose insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylketonuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Juandice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic fibrosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":17611,"text":"A woman presents to the emergency department with a complaint of severe abdominal pain, and constipation for a few days. She is a mother to 4 children all born via c-section. What could be the cause of her condition?","explanation":"**Adhesive small bowel disease**, also known as adhesive small bowel obstruction, occurs when the intestines become stuck together or to the wall of the abdomen due to bands of tissue (adhesions) that form after surgery. Given the woman's history of **multiple cesarean sections**, she would be at an increased risk of developing these adhesions, making adhesive small bowel disease a probable diagnosis for her symptoms.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Ulcerative colitis** is a chronic inflammatory condition affecting the colon (large intestine) primarily. It presents with symptoms like diarrhea mixed with blood, abdominal pain, and urgency to defecate. While it can cause abdominal pain, the history provided does not strongly suggest this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nCrohn disease can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from the mouth to the anus. Symptoms can include abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, and fatigue. Like ulcerative colitis, while it can cause abdominal pain, the clinical picture does not align perfectly with the history given.\r\n\r\nInflammatory bowel disease encompasses both ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease. It would not be the most specific diagnosis in this patient.\r\n\r\nWhile abdominal pain and constipation can be symptoms associated with some gastrointestinal malignancies, there is no specific evidence from the provided history that strongly points to a carcinoma.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 777-778.","responses":[{"text":"Carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adhesive small bowel disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18571,"text":"Which of the following is described as taking a detailed record of a person's dietary habits, anthropometric measurements, and physical exam findings to figure out the individual need for nutrition based on dietary preference?","explanation":"**Nutritional assessment** involves a detailed evaluation of both objective and subjective data related to an individual's food and nutrient intake, lifestyle, and medical history. Anthropometric measurements, physical examination findings, and dietary preferences are all parts of a nutritional assessment.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nNutritional treatment refers to the intervention or plan designed to address a person's specific nutritional needs. While it can be based on the information gathered during a nutritional assessment, the treatment itself is an actionable plan rather than the process of gathering data.\r\n\r\nDifferential diagnosis is a method used by health professionals to diagnose a specific disease or condition from a set of potential diagnoses based on symptomatology and diagnostic test findings. It is not specific to dietary habits or nutrition.\r\n\r\nNutritional diagnosis involves identifying and labeling a nutrition problem that can be resolved or improved through nutrition intervention. It does not specifically encompass the comprehensive gathering of data described.\r\n\r\nHealth and lifestyle goals are the specific aims or objectives set by an individual or with the help of a healthcare professional to improve or maintain their health and well-being. It is a part of goal-setting but does not involve the comprehensive evaluation mentioned in the description.","reference":"Kesari A, Noel JY. Nutritional assessment. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 28, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK580496/","responses":[{"text":"Nutritional assessment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional diagnosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Health and lifestyle goals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Differential diagnosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18575,"text":"Early starvation causes transient changes in basal metabolic rate. With long-standing starvation, which of the following is correct regarding BMR in long-standing starvation?","explanation":"In the initial stages of starvation, the body might increase its energy expenditure to find food. However, with prolonged starvation, the body conserves energy, and **BMR decreases**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBMR is the rate at which the body expends energy or burns calories at rest. Various factors, including physical activity and energy expenditure, can influence it.\r\n\r\nNutritional status plays a crucial role in determining BMR. For instance, malnourished individuals often have a reduced BMR as the body tries to conserve energy.\r\n\r\nDietary changes, especially the intake of certain foods, can increase or decrease BMR temporarily. For instance, caffeine and spicy foods can temporarily raise BMR.","reference":"Devlin MJ. Why does starvation make bones fat? American journal of human biology : the official journal of the Human Biology Council. Published September 2011. Accessed August 28, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3169094/","responses":[{"text":"BMR is not affected by energy expenditure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BMR is not affected by dietary changes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BMR is not affected by the nutritional status of an individual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BMR increases in long standing starvation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BMR decreases in long standing starvation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18617,"text":"A patient presented to the outpatient department with reports that were positive for viral hepatitis. What type of jaundice can be seen in this patient?","explanation":"In a patient with viral hepatitis, the type of jaundice most commonly seen is **hepatocellular jaundice**. This form of jaundice arises when there is damage to the liver cells, impairing the liver's ability to process bilirubin. Viral hepatitis leads to inflammation and damage of the hepatocytes, which are the liver cells responsible for the metabolism and excretion of bilirubin.\r\n\r\n**Jaundice due to Gilbert syndrome** is a result of a benign hereditary condition that affects the enzyme responsible for processing bilirubin. It's not caused by viral hepatitis or liver damage.\r\n\r\n**Jaundice due to sickle cell disease** is related to hemolysis, or the breakdown of red blood cells, leading to an increase in bilirubin. It is not due to direct liver damage.\r\n\r\n**Obstructive jaundice** is a result of a blockage in the bile ducts, preventing the excretion of bilirubin from the liver to the intestines. It's not typically seen with viral hepatitis unless there's an additional complication.\r\n\r\n**Hemolytic jaundice** arises when there is rapid breakdown of red blood cells, leading to an increased production of bilirubin. It is not directly caused by viral hepatitis.","reference":"Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 29, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544252/","responses":[{"text":"Hepatocellular jaundice","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jaundice due to Gilbert syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jaundice due to sickle cell disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18618,"text":"A 40-year-old female patient presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of aching pain in the abdomen anorexia, weight loss, pale stools, and dark-colored urine. Which of the following symptoms in this patient indicate obstructive jaundice?","explanation":"In **obstructive jaundice**, there's a blockage in the ducts that transport bile from the liver to the intestines. This leads to bilirubin (a component of bile) being retained in the body, causing the skin and eyes to turn yellow (jaundice). Because bilirubin isn't reaching the intestines, the **stool becomes pale or clay-colored**. The excess bilirubin in the body gets filtered by the kidneys, leading to **dark-colored urine**.\r\n\r\nAnorexia, in this context referring to loss of appetite, can be seen in various conditions including liver diseases, but is not specific for obstructive jaundice.\r\n\r\nAging is a general process and is not directly related to obstructive jaundice.\r\n\r\nWeight loss can be a feature of many illnesses, including cancers that could lead to obstructive jaundice, but on its own, it does not indicate the condition.\r\n\r\nPain in the abdomen can be seen in cases of obstructive jaundice, especially if the cause is gallstones or a tumor blocking the bile ducts. However, abdominal pain can be seen in many gastrointestinal conditions and is not specific to obstructive jaundice.","reference":"Coucke EM, Akbar H, Kahloon A, Lopez PP. Biliary obstruction. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 29, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539698/","responses":[{"text":"Pale-stools and dark-urine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anorexia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pain in abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18907,"text":"A one-week-old girl was brought to the emergency department with severe hypoxemia, tachypnea, and costal retractions. History from the family revealed cyanosis, apnea, and occasional arching of the back especially during the feeds, which further worsens the symptoms. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for the one-week-old girl with the described symptoms, especially the worsening of symptoms during feeds, is **gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)**. In infants, GERD can present with a variety of symptoms, including **recurrent vomiting, irritability, arching of the back (especially during or right after feeds), apnea, and respiratory symptoms like coughing, wheezing**, and even severe presentations like **cyanosis**. The correlation of symptoms with feeding, the arching of the back, and the respiratory symptoms strongly point towards GERD.\r\n\r\nCerebral concussion refers to a traumatic brain injury typically following a blow to the head.\r\n\r\nCentral hypoventilation syndrome is a disorder of autonomic control of breathing, where the body doesn't respond properly to low levels of oxygen or high levels of carbon dioxide in the blood. While it can cause cyanosis and apnea, the specific relationship of symptoms with feeding and the arching of the back don't align well with this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nRespiratory chain disease refers to mitochondrial disorders affecting cellular energy production. Though they can present with a variety of systemic symptoms, the specific clinical picture described here does not point strongly toward this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nIn neonates, meningitis might present with fever, irritability, lethargy, poor feeding, and a bulging fontanelle.","reference":"Ledersnaider M, Kreilein N, Triplett R, Peterman NJ. Gastroesophageal reflux disease in a one-week-old infant presenting with cyanosis and respiratory distress. Cureus. Accessed September 2, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9524716/","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory chain disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central hypoventilation syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral concussion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroesophageal reflux disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18908,"text":"A forensic professor presents a case of a 30-year-old man with a history of head injury and cerebral concussion, who was admitted to an isolated room with his body curled up in the bed and his head under pillows. She further said that this kind of patient dislikes any interference or exposure to light. These patients are not unconscious but pay no attention to their surroundings, and are liable to become aggressive if disturbed. What is the most likely condition in this case?","explanation":"**Cerebral irritation** is a condition where the brain is in a state of **heightened sensitivity following trauma**. Patients often display an aversion to stimuli like light and sound and may prefer to remain in a quiet, dark environment. While they are not unconscious, they can appear disinterested or unresponsive to their surroundings. Disturbing these patients can result in aggressive behavior due to their heightened sensitivity.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPost-concussion syndrome is a complex disorder that can occur after a person has suffered a concussion. Its symptoms can include headaches, dizziness, fatigue, and irritability, but the presentation described in the case is more consistent with cerebral irritation.\r\n\r\nCerebral concussion is a traumatic brain injury that affects brain function. While it can present with a variety of symptoms, including confusion, amnesia, and headaches, the description provided best matches cerebral irritation.\r\n\r\nCerebral contusion refers to a bruise of brain tissue, often associated with swelling and bleeding. The symptoms might include a headache, confusion, and neurological deficits, but the case scenario does not predominantly point towards this diagnosis.\r\n\r\nPost traumatic condition is a vague term and can encompass a variety of post-injury syndromes, but the specific behaviors and symptoms described align best with cerebral irritation.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides 2024, GIT-II, Forensic Medicine, Topic: Regional Injuries-Brain.","responses":[{"text":"Cerebral irritation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Post traumatic condition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral concussion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post concussion syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18911,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect about the action of the following drugs?","explanation":"**Milk alkali syndrome** is actually caused by the excessive consumption of **calcium carbonate**, typically when taken in large amounts for the treatment of peptic ulcer disease or as a dietary supplement. This can result in hypercalcemia, metabolic alkalosis, and renal insufficiency. **Magnesium hydroxide**, on the other hand, is an antacid and **laxative**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAluminium hydroxide does cause constipation.\r\n\r\nAbsorption of calcium carbonate can be affected by the consumption of omeprazole since omeprazole reduces stomach acid and calcium carbonate requires an acidic environment for optimal absorption.\r\n\r\nSucralfate is used for the treatment of duodenal ulcers. It acts by forming a protective barrier over the ulcer, shielding it from stomach acid and allowing it to heal.\r\n\r\nOmeprazole does inhibit the release of stomach acid. It is a proton pump inhibitor that reduces the production of stomach acid by binding to the enzyme in the wall of the stomach that produces acid.","reference":"Karen Whalen, et al. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed., Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2019: 543, 544, 545.","responses":[{"text":"Omeprazole inhibits the release of stomach acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorption of calcium carbonate is affected by the consumption of omeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sucralfate is effective for the treatment of duodenal ulcers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminium hydrooxide causes constipation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Milk alkali syndrome is caused by magnesium hydroxide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18915,"text":"A 60-year-old alcoholic male comes to the medical outpatient department with dilated veins in his abdominal region. He has a history of portal hypertension. What is this condition called?","explanation":"**Caput medusa** refers to the appearance of **dilated, engorged paraumbilical veins**, which radiate from the umbilicus across the abdomen due to portal hypertension. The name \"Caput medusa\" is derived from the resemblance of these veins to the head of Medusa, a figure in Greek mythology with snakes for hair.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nMelena, on the other hand, refers to black, tarry stools that are indicative of upper gastrointestinal bleeding. Hematemesis is when a person vomits blood, and this can be a consequence of conditions like peptic ulcers or esophageal varices. Spider angiomata are small, red vascular lesions that can be seen on the skin and are associated with liver disease. Lastly, Fetor hepaticus is a unique breath odor, often described as a sweet, musty aroma, associated with chronic liver disease.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier, 2015: 830.","responses":[{"text":"Hematemesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spider angiomata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Melena","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fetor hepaticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caput medusa","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18943,"text":"Which of the following is not the cause of extreme weakness and malnutrition in liver cirrhosis?","explanation":"In liver cirrhosis, extreme weakness and malnutrition are not caused by **metabolic changes characterized by reduced energy expenditure**.\r\n\r\nAnorexia and liver decompensation can lead to poor dietary intake, contributing to malnutrition.\r\n\r\nProtein catabolism can result in muscle wasting and weakness.\r\n\r\nReduced glycogen storage can compromise energy reserves.\r\n\r\nAn accelerated starvation response can lead to rapid utilization of stored nutrients, exacerbating weakness and malnutrition.","reference":"Chapman B, Sinclair M, Gow PJ, Testro AG. Malnutrition in cirrhosis: More food for thought. World Journal of Hepatology. Published November 27, 2020. Accessed September 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7701970/","responses":[{"text":"Protein catabolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic changes characterized by reduced energy expenditure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anorexia and liver decompensation leading to poor dietary intake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced glycogen storage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accelerated starvation response","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18947,"text":"In a clinically stable patient, immediate exploratory laparotomy is indicated in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"In a clinically stable patient, **immediate exploratory laparotomy** is indicated for **penetrating wounds in the thoracoabdominal region.** Such injuries have a high likelihood of damaging internal organs, and timely surgical intervention is crucial to ascertain and repair any internal damage, even if the patient initially appears stable. \r\n\r\nForeign bodies, depending on their nature and location, may or may not require surgical intervention.\r\n\r\nAn intestinal mass on CT requires further diagnostic evaluation.\r\n\r\nFractures typically do not necessitate a laparotomy unless associated with other intra-abdominal injuries.\r\n\r\nPartial obstruction, if stable, may be managed conservatively before considering surgery.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, D24, Gastrointestinal Module, Surgery, Topic: Abdominal Trauma.","responses":[{"text":"Penetrating wounds in thoracoabdominal reion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Foriegn body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal mass on CT","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Partial obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fractures","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18951,"text":"Which of the following options correctly states the management of subacute partial small bowel obstruction?","explanation":"In the management of **subacute partial small bowel obstruction**, patients are given **intravenous hydration** to maintain hydration levels. They are advised not to eat or drink (NPO) to prevent complications from the obstruction. A **nasogastric tube** is used for decompression, removing air and fluids from the stomach to alleviate symptoms. **Continuous monitoring** assesses the patient's response to treatment, ensuring timely adjustments if needed. This conservative approach aims for bowel recovery without immediate surgery while ensuring patient safety.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nLower gastrointestinal endoscopy is generally not a primary intervention for managing bowel obstruction. It involves visualization of the rectum and distal colon and is used more for diagnostic purposes in other conditions.\r\n\r\nWhile nasogastric decompression is part of the management, colonoscopy itself is not typically used in the initial management of small bowel obstruction. It is used more for the diagnosis and management of colonic diseases.\r\n\r\nExploratory laparotomy (a surgical operation where the abdomen is opened and the organs examined) would be considered in cases where there's a complete obstruction, strangulation, or other complications, not for a subacute partial obstruction without complications.\r\n\r\nUpper gastrointestinal endoscopy is a procedure where a flexible tube with a camera is passed through the mouth to visualize the esophagus, stomach, and the first part of the small intestine. It is typically used for diagnostic purposes for upper GI conditions and not as a primary management tool for small bowel obstruction.","reference":"Vercruysse G, Busch R, Dimcheff D, et al. Table 4, non-operative medical management for sbo. Published April 2021. Accessed September 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK572336/table/fm.s1.t3/","responses":[{"text":"Exploratory laparotomy and NPO","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous hydration, NPO, nasogastric decompression, monitoring","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colonoscopy and nasogastric decompression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower gastrointestinal endoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19026,"text":"Which of the following is a precursor to the histamine?","explanation":"Histamine is derived from the amino acid **histidine**.\r\n\r\n**Phenylalanine** is an essential amino acid that is a precursor for another amino acid, tyrosine. Phenylalanine is also involved in the production of neurotransmitters like dopamine, epinephrine, and norepinephrine.\r\n\r\n**Tryptophan** is an essential amino acid that is a precursor for the neurotransmitter serotonin, as well as for the hormone melatonin.\r\n\r\n**Alanine** is a non-essential amino acid that plays a role in transferring nitrogen from peripheral tissues to the liver.\r\n\r\n**Tyrosine** is a non-essential amino acid that is involved in the production of several important substances in the body, including dopamine, epinephrine, norepinephrine, and thyroid hormones.","reference":"Huang H, Li Y, Liang J, Finkelman FD. Molecular regulation of histamine synthesis. Frontiers in Immunology. Published June 20, 2018. Accessed September 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6019440/","responses":[{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alanine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tryptophan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylalanine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19030,"text":"A 55-year-old male patient presents to the clinic with complaints of difficulty in swallowing and food getting stuck in the esophagus for the past month. He has a history of gastroesophageal reflux disease for five years but isn't compliant with his medication. He is a smoker, and his BMI is 32 kg/m2. He undergoes endoscopy, which reveals intestinal metaplasia in the lower one-third of the esophagus. Which of the following is associated with this condition?","explanation":"**Barrett esophagus** refers to intestinal metaplasia in the lower one-third of the esophagus. It is a complication of chronic **gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)** and is associated with an increased risk of developing esophageal adenocarcinoma.\r\n\r\n**Esophageal adenocarcinoma** is a type of cancer that arises from the glandular cells located in the lower part of the esophagus. It is commonly associated with Barret esophagus, especially in individuals with risk factors like GERD, obesity (as indicated by the patient's BMI), and smoking.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nZenker's diverticulum is an outpouching of the lining of the esophagus that occurs at the junction of the esophagus and the pharynx. It can cause difficulty swallowing, but it is not directly associated with intestinal metaplasia.\r\n\r\nInfectious esophagitis can occur due to various pathogens, including viruses, fungi, and bacteria. It can cause difficulty in swallowing and can be seen on endoscopy, but it doesn't typically result in intestinal metaplasia.\r\n\r\nEsophageal squamous cell carcinoma is another primary type of esophageal cancer. It originates from the squamous cells that line the esophagus. It is more commonly associated with alcohol and tobacco use but is not directly linked to Barrett's esophagus or intestinal metaplasia.\r\n\r\nHelicobacter pylori infection primarily affects the stomach and can lead to gastric ulcers, chronic gastritis, and even gastric adenocarcinoma. It is not directly linked to intestinal metaplasia of the esophagus.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015:  758.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infectious esophagitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicobacter pylori infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zenker's diverticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19041,"text":"A 60-year-old male patient presented to the outpatient department with complaints of recurrent attacks of right upper quadrant pain, nausea, vomiting, and intolerance for fatty food. His biopsy reports that were done previously showed that the gallbladder wall was variably thickened, and had an opaque gray-white appearance along with buried crypts of epithelium within the gallbladder wall. Outpouchings of the mucosal epithelium through the wall were also visible. Which of the following conditions is closely associated with the above-mentioned symptoms?","explanation":"The condition closely associated with the symptoms described, particularly recurrent attacks of right upper quadrant pain, intolerance for fatty food, and the gallbladder biopsy findings, is **cholelithiasis**.\r\n\r\nCholelithiasis refers to the presence of stones in the gallbladder. The symptoms described, like right upper quadrant pain, nausea, and vomiting, especially after consuming fatty foods, are characteristic of gallstone attacks. The biopsy findings of a **variably thickened gallbladder wall, an opaque gray-white appearance**, and **outpouchings of the mucosal epithelium (Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses)** further confirm the diagnosis of cholelithiasis.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nUlcerative colitis is an inflammatory bowel disease affecting primarily the colon, causing bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, and other systemic symptoms. It's not closely related to the gallbladder findings described.\r\n\r\nCrohn's disease is another type of inflammatory bowel disease that can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract. While it can involve the gallbladder, the described findings are more consistent with cholelithiasis.\r\n\r\nAcute viral hepatitis primarily affects the liver, leading to jaundice, malaise, and anorexia. It doesn't directly result in gallbladder stones or the described pathology.\r\n\r\nPrimary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) involves inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts. While PSC can be associated with gallbladder pathology, the described symptoms and biopsy findings are more consistent with cholelithiasis.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 879.","responses":[{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute viral hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19051,"text":"Which of the following is the extra-intestinal manifestation of ulcerative colitis?","explanation":"**Ulcerative colitis** is a type of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that primarily affects the colon. While its primary symptoms relate to the gastrointestinal tract, such as bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, and urgency to defecate, it can also have systemic manifestations. \r\n\r\n**Arthritis**, or inflammation of the joints, is one of the most common **extra-intestinal manifestations** of ulcerative colitis. The joint pain often mirrors the activity of the bowel disease; that is, the arthritis may flare up during a colitis flare and lessen during remission.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nEsophagitis is inflammation of the esophagus. It can result from several causes, including acid reflux, infections, and certain medications, but it's not directly linked to ulcerative colitis.\r\n\r\nPancreatitis refers to inflammation of the pancreas. Although rare, some IBD patients can develop pancreatitis, often related to medications or gallstones, but it is not a typical extra-intestinal manifestation of ulcerative colitis.\r\n\r\nGlucose-6-phosphate deficiency is an inherited condition that affects red blood cells, leading to hemolysis. It is not associated with ulcerative colitis.\r\n\r\nEncephalopathy encompasses a broad term for any brain disease that alters brain function or structure. It is not a typical extra-intestinal manifestation of ulcerative colitis.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Esophaitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucoe-6-phosphate deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Encephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19052,"text":"Which of the following drugs for treating hepatitis has nephrotoxic effects?","explanation":"**Adefovir** is known to have nephrotoxic effects and requires dose-adjustment in renal insufficiency.\r\n\r\nTelbivudine, entecavir, and lamivudine are antiviral drugs used to treat hepatitis B infections. They have different side effect profiles, but nephrotoxicity is not a primary concern for these drugs. \r\n\r\nInterferon-alpha is an immunomodulatory agent used in the treatment of various conditions including hepatitis B and C. It has a range of side effects, but it is not primarily known for nephrotoxicity.","reference":"Karen Whalen, et al. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed., Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2019: 439.","responses":[{"text":"Entecavir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenofovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Telbivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19054,"text":"Which of the following can be used in the treatment of human immunodeficiency virus as a part of antiretroviral therapy in case of a high degree of resistance to lamivudine and emtricitabine?","explanation":"**Tenofovir** can be used in the treatment of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) as a part of antiretroviral therapy, especially when there is a high degree of resistance to lamivudine and emtricitabine. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAcyclovir is an antiviral agent primarily used for herpes simplex and varicella-zoster virus infections. Darunavir and Indinavir are protease inhibitors and are also used in the management of HIV, but not specifically for resistance to lamivudine and emtricitabine. Adefovir is primarily used in the treatment of hepatitis B virus infection.","reference":"Karen Whalen, et al. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed., Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2019: 447.","responses":[{"text":"Tenofovir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acyclovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Darunavir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"lndinavir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19055,"text":"Which of the following drugs can be prescribed to sensitize a patient who wishes to leave alcohol addiction?","explanation":"**Disulfiram** can be prescribed to sensitize a patient who wishes to leave alcohol addiction. When a person takes disulfiram and then consumes alcohol, they experience unpleasant symptoms, including facial flushing, headache, nausea, and vomiting. This reaction serves as a deterrent for drinking while on the medication. The intention is that over time, the individual associates alcohol consumption with these negative symptoms and is thereby discouraged from drinking.","reference":"Karen Whalen, et al. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed., Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2019: 599.","responses":[{"text":"Ethanol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthetic cannabinoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disulfiram","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysergic acid diethylamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthetic cathinone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19056,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with complaints of jaundice, pruritus, and skin xanthomas. The senior doctor says that biopsy reports of the patient show elongated green-brown plugs of bile visible in dilated bile canaliculi. Some canaliculi are ruptured, which causes extravasation of bile, and droplets of bile pigment accumulated within hepatocytes, show a foamy appearance, also called feathery degeneration. Which of the following laboratory investigations can confirm the diagnosis of cholestasis?","explanation":"**Elevated serum alkaline phosphatase and γ-glutamyl transpeptidase** can confirm the diagnosis of cholestasis. **Cholestasis** is a condition where there is impaired bile flow. Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and γ-glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT) are enzymes that are located on the bile canaliculi in the liver. In cases of cholestasis, these enzymes spill into the bloodstream and lead to elevated levels. Elevated levels of these enzymes, especially in the presence of the described clinical and histological findings, are indicative of cholestasis.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 853, 854.","responses":[{"text":"Reduced levels of carbonic anhydrase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated serum alkaline phosphatase and γ-glutamyl transpeptidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased liver enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised unconjugated bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated level of isocitrate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20211,"text":"Which of the following antiviral drugs used in the treatment of hepatitis is most likely to cause anemia in the patient?","explanation":"**Ribavirin** is the antiviral drug used in the treatment of hepatitis that is most likely to cause **anemia** in the patient.\r\n\r\nAdefovir is an antiviral drug used primarily for the treatment of hepatitis B. The main side effects include nephrotoxicity and lactic acidosis.\r\n  \r\nInterferon α is used in the treatment of various conditions, including hepatitis B and C. Its side effects include flu-like symptoms, depression, and neutropenia, among others.\r\n\r\nLetermovir is primarily used for the prevention of cytomegalovirus (CMV) infection in transplant patients and is not commonly associated with anemia.\r\n\r\nAcyclovir is an antiviral used mainly for herpes viruses, including herpes simplex and varicella-zoster. Its primary side effects are related to kidney function and the central nervous system.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 422.","responses":[{"text":"Interferon α","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acyclovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Letermovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribavirin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20213,"text":"Which of the following is the most relevant statement regarding the H2 receptor blockers?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Nugent CC, Falkson SR, Terrell JM. H2 Blockers. [Updated 2023 Aug 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525994/\r\n(2) Begg M, Tarhuni M, N. Fotso M, et al. Comparing the safety and efficacy of proton pump inhibitors and histamine-2 receptor antagonists in the management of patients with peptic ulcer disease: a systematic review. Cureus. Published August 29, 2023. Accessed January 11, 2024. https://www.cureus.com/articles/163652-comparing-the-safety-and-efficacy-of-proton-pump-inhibitors-and-histamine-2-receptor-antagonists-in-the-management-of-patients-with-peptic-ulcer-disease-a-systematic-review","responses":[{"text":"They avoid first pass effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They cause fastest healing of duodenal ulcers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are most efficacious drug in inhibiting gastric acid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They afford most prompt relief of ulcer pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are commonly used drug to decrease gastric acid secretion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20214,"text":"Which of the following drugs causes non-competitive inhibition of the H2 receptors?","explanation":"**Loxtidine** causes **non-competitive** inhibition of the H2 receptors.\r\n\r\n- **Cimetidine, famotidine, nizatidine,** and **ranitidine** are all H2 receptor antagonists, but they exert their effects through competitive inhibition of the H2 receptors, meaning they compete with histamine for binding to these receptors. In contrast, non-competitive inhibitors like loxtidine bind to the receptor at a site other than the active site and change the receptor's conformation, making it less responsive to its substrate.","reference":"Mills JG, Wood JR. The pharmacology of histamine H2-receptor antagonists. Methods Find Exp Clin Pharmacol. 1989;11 Suppl 1:87-95.\r\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2566729/","responses":[{"text":"Loxtidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raxonatidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rinitidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nazitidine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20381,"text":"Age and gender are found in which graphical representation in the form of histogram?","explanation":"The graphical representation that displays **age and gender** in the form of a histogram is the **population pyramid**. Typically, it is a two-sided histogram where one side represents the male population and the other side represents the female population, with age groups stacked vertically from youngest at the bottom to oldest at the top.\r\n\r\nThe epidemiological triangle represents the triad of host, agent, and environment in understanding disease causation.\r\n\r\nWheel of causation takes into account the complex interplay between host factors, environmental factors, and biological agents in disease causation.\r\n\r\nWeb of causation recognizes that many interrelated factors contribute to disease causation and health outcomes.\r\n\r\nBimodal histogram represents a data distribution that has two different peaks or modes. It doesn't specifically represent age and gender like a population pyramid does.","reference":"Ilyas M. Public Health and Community Medicine. 7th ed. Time Publishers; 2006: 93.","responses":[{"text":"Bimodal histogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemiological triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Web of causation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wheel of causation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population pyramid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20383,"text":"A 15-year-old boy with suspected acute appendicitis has an Alvarado score of 5-6. Which of the following would be the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","explanation":"The **Alvarado score** is used to stratify the risk of **acute appendicitis** based on clinical findings and laboratory tests. Scores range from 1 to 10. Patients with scores:\r\n\r\n- 1-4 are considered to have a low probability of appendicitis. Observation and reassessment are recommended.\r\n- 5-6 are in a moderate probability category. These patients typically undergo imaging, usually with a **CT scan**, to further evaluate for appendicitis.\r\n- 7-10 are at high probability, and these patients typically go directly to surgery without the need for imaging.","reference":"(1) O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, Sayers RD, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2023: 1341-1342.\r\n  \r\n(2) Ozsoy, Zeki, and Erdinc Yenidogan. “Evaluation of the Alvarado Scoring System in the Management of Acute Appendicitis.” Turkish Journal of Surgery, 8 Sept. 2017, http://www.turkjsurg.com/abstract/1493/eng.","responses":[{"text":"Open appendectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clinical management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conservative management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computerized tomography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diagnostic laparoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20385,"text":"A 30-year-old man presented to the outpatient department with complaints of bleeding per rectum for 2 years. On colonoscopy, there was a diffuse inflammation of the rectum and sigmoid colon with superficial mucosal ulcers. A biopsy was performed. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Ulcerative colitis** is an inflammatory bowel disease that affects the innermost lining of the large intestine (colon) and rectum. It presents as continuous inflammation, starting from the rectum and may extend proximally to involve other parts of the colon. Symptoms include **rectal bleeding, abdominal pain, and diarrhea**. The presence of **superficial mucosal ulcers** in the rectum and sigmoid colon seen on colonoscopy, along with the clinical symptoms, strongly suggest this diagnosis.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Colon polyps** are small clumps of cells that form on the lining of the colon. Most polyps are benign, but over time, some types of polyps can develop into colon cancer. Colonoscopy may reveal polyps as raised or pedunculated lesions, but they don't typically cause diffuse inflammation or superficial mucosal ulcers.\r\n\r\n**Colon cancer** usually presents with symptoms like change in bowel habits, persistent abdominal discomfort, and blood in the stool, among others. On colonoscopy, a discrete mass or lesion would be more typical, rather than diffuse inflammation.\r\n\r\n**Intestinal tuberculosis** is an extrapulmonary form of tuberculosis and can mimic Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis. It might present with ulcers on colonoscopy, but these ulcers are typically deeper and may have a more segmental distribution. Additionally, the involvement of other parts of the GI tract or systemic signs of TB would also give clues to this diagnosis.\r\n\r\n**Crohn's disease** can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus. Unlike ulcerative colitis, which has continuous involvement, Crohn's disease tends to be transmural (affecting all layers of the bowel wall) and can show a \"skip\" pattern on imaging or colonoscopy, with healthy tissue between areas of diseased tissue. The ulcers in Crohn's can be deeper, often described as \"knife-like\" ulcers.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 803.","responses":[{"text":"Colon cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon polyp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chron's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20386,"text":"Secretions of which of the following is totally under neuronal control?","explanation":"The secretions of the **salivary gland** are totally under **neuronal control**. Salivary secretion is governed by both the sympathetic and parasympathetic divisions of the autonomic nervous system. While the **parasympathetic stimulation** (primarily through the facial and glossopharyngeal nerves) increases the volume of watery saliva, **sympathetic stimulation** tends to produce a smaller volume of more viscous saliva. The other organs listed have hormonal influences on their secretions in addition to any neuronal controls.","reference":"Costanzo LS. BRS: Physiology. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019. 207.","responses":[{"text":"Intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salivary gland","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20389,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents to the emergency with complaints of nausea, and right upper quadrant pain. There is no history of jaundice. Laboratory investigations reveal a total leucocyte count (TLC) of 12,000 cells/dl with 91% neutrophils. Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's condition?","explanation":"**Acute cholecystitis** refers to inflammation of the gallbladder and is commonly associated with gallstones blocking the cystic duct. The inflammation can result in right upper quadrant pain, fever, and leukocytosis.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Primary sclerosing cholangitis** is a condition where there is a chronic inflammation of the bile ducts leading to their scarring and narrowing. Patients might present with jaundice, itching, and abdominal pain.\r\n\r\n**Acute liver failure** is a rapid decline in liver function and can be caused by a variety of factors, including drugs, viruses, or toxins. Symptoms include jaundice, confusion (from hepatic encephalopathy), and bleeding, among others. \r\n\r\n**Acute cholangitis** refers to an infection of the bile ducts, typically caused by bacteria ascending from the duodenum. It is characterized by right upper quadrant pain, fever, and jaundice (known as Charcot's triad). The absence of jaundice in the patient's presentation makes this diagnosis less likely.\r\n\r\n**Hepatitis A** is a viral liver infection. It can lead to symptoms like jaundice, fatigue, and abdominal pain. The mode of transmission is usually fecal-oral, often from contaminated food or water. While hepatitis A can cause right upper quadrant pain and nausea, the clinical picture described is more consistent with acute cholecystitis.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 905.","responses":[{"text":"Acute cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute liver failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20392,"text":"A 35-year-old patient presents to the clinic with crampy abdominal pain, flatulence, and constipation. Which of the following should be avoided in order to improve the symptoms in this patient?","explanation":"In the context of the symptoms described, which are consistent with **irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)** or other functional gastrointestinal disorders, the patient may benefit from reducing the intake of foods rich in **fermentable oligosaccharides, disaccharides, monosaccharides, and polyols (FODMAPs)**. **Bread** is the one that often contains high amounts of FODMAPs, specifically from wheat. Reducing wheat-based bread intake might help improve the symptoms in this patient. \r\n\r\n**Lignin**, **pectin**, **cellulose**, and **mucilage** are all dietary fibers. Generally, dietary fiber is beneficial for constipation and overall gut health. However, in individuals with certain gastrointestinal conditions, adjusting the type or amount of fiber intake might be necessary based on individual tolerances.","reference":"Ohlsson, Bodil. “Theories behind the Effect of Starch‑ and Sucrose‑reduced Diets on Gastrointestinal Symptoms in Irritable Bowel Syndrome (Review).” Molecular Medicine Reports, 16 Aug. 2021, http://www.spandidos-publications.com/10.3892/mmr.2021.12372.","responses":[{"text":"Lignin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bread","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cellulose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20395,"text":"Which of the following is used to calculate the amount of body fat, by using the weight and height, and is different in males and females?","explanation":"The **body mass index (BMI)** is used to calculate the amount of body fat based on weight and height. It provides a general indication of whether a person has a healthy body weight for a person of their height. The formula is the same for males and females, but the interpretation of the values might vary between genders and different age groups.","reference":"Nuttall, Frank Q. “Body Mass Index: Obesity, BMI, and Health A Critical Review.” Nutrition Today, May 2015, https://journals.lww.com/00017285-201505000-00005.","responses":[{"text":"Basal metabolic rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Waist-hip ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Waist circumference","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body fat scale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20397,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents to the emergency department with generalized abdominal pain and board-like rigidity. He has a history of chronic NSAID use.  An abdominal X-ray reveals air under the diaphragm. Which of the following conditions is most likely the cause of this patient's condition?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with generalized abdominal pain, board-like rigidity, and the finding of air under the diaphragm on abdominal X-ray is indicative of **perforation of a hollow viscus** leading to **pneumoperitoneum**. Given the **history of chronic NSAID use**, the most likely cause of this perforation is a **duodenal ulcer rupture**. NSAIDs are well-known risk factors for peptic ulcers, which include both gastric and duodenal ulcers. When these ulcers perforate, they can lead to the release of air into the peritoneal cavity, which can then be detected as free air under the diaphragm on imaging.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Duodenal atresia** is a congenital condition where a part of the duodenum fails to develop properly, leading to an obstruction. Infants with this condition often present with bilious vomiting shortly after birth. It does not cause pneumoperitoneum.\r\n\r\n**Boerhaave lesion**, also known as spontaneous esophageal rupture, is caused by a sudden increase in intra-esophageal pressure, such as during forceful vomiting. While this can lead to air in the mediastinum and potentially the pleural cavity, it does not typically lead to free air under the diaphragm.\r\n\r\n**Gastric ulcer rupture**: Similar to duodenal ulcer rupture, a perforated gastric ulcer can indeed lead to pneumoperitoneum with air under the diaphragm. However, duodenal ulcers are more commonly associated with NSAID use and are more likely to perforate than gastric ulcers.\r\n\r\n**Mallory-Weiss tears**: These are longitudinal mucosal tears at the gastroesophageal junction, commonly associated with persistent vomiting. While they can cause hematemesis (vomiting of blood), they do not result in perforation or air under the diaphragm.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 801.","responses":[{"text":"Gastric ulcer rupture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Boerhaave lesion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal ulcer rupture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal artesia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory weiss tears","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20400,"text":"A 30-year-old alcoholic is brought to the emergency department with blood-containing vomit. He is given adequate treatment. After a few days, an upper gastrointestinal endoscopy is performed which reveals healed longitudinal tears in the lower third of the esophagus. Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's condition?","explanation":"**Mallory-Weiss tears** occur due to severe and persistent vomiting, often in the context of alcohol abuse or binge drinking. This repeated vomiting causes a sudden rise in intra-abdominal pressure leading to these longitudinal mucosal tears at the gastroesophageal junction. The tears can result in **hematemesis (vomiting of blood)** but usually heal on their own over time.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSquamous cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that originates from the squamous cells in the esophagus. It does not cause tears but would present with progressive dysphagia (difficulty swallowing) and weight loss. On endoscopy, a tumor, not tears, would be visualized.\r\n\r\nBoerhaave syndrome, also known as spontaneous esophageal rupture, is a severe condition resulting from violent vomiting, leading to a tear in the esophagus. While it involves vomiting and potential tearing, the tear typically extends through all layers of the esophagus, leading to leaking of esophageal contents into the mediastinum. This condition is more severe than what is described in the scenario and would not present as a healed tear on endoscopy.\r\n\r\nSchatzki's rings are circumferential rings found in the lower esophagus. They can cause episodic difficulty swallowing solid foods but are not associated with vomiting blood. On endoscopy, these appear as rings and not tears.\r\n\r\nAdenocarcinoma is another type of esophageal cancer that originates from glandular cells, typically in the distal esophagus or gastroesophageal junction. On endoscopy, it would be visualized as a mass or tumor, not as healed tears.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 758.","responses":[{"text":"Boerhaave syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory Weiss tears","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schatzki's rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20401,"text":"A 30-year-old female is brought to the emergency room with severe abdominal pain. Two years ago, the woman had a lower gastrointestinal endoscopy, which revealed skip lesions and serpentine ulcers in the colon. Her pulse is 120 beats per minute. X-ray reveals air under the diaphragm. Which of the following conditions is most likely the cause of the current symptoms of the patient?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the current symptoms of the patient, given the presentation of severe abdominal pain, tachycardia, and the X-ray finding of air under the diaphragm, is **bowel perforation.**  This is a surgical emergency, as the perforation allows contents from the intestine to leak into the peritoneal cavity, leading to peritonitis. The **presence of air under the diaphragm (pneumoperitoneum)** on X-ray is a classic sign of a **perforated viscus**, usually the bowel.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nEntero-colonic fistula refers to a connection between the small intestine and colon. While this could be a complication of conditions like Crohn's disease (which the skip lesions and serpentine ulcers might suggest), it doesn't typically lead to air under the diaphragm.\r\n\r\nEntero-vesicular fistula is a connection between the bowel and the urinary bladder. Symptoms might include recurrent urinary tract infections and pneumaturia (air in the urine) but would not cause air under the diaphragm.\r\n\r\nFat necrosis refers to the death of adipose tissue, often seen in the context of pancreatitis. It doesn't produce air under the diaphragm.\r\n\r\nEntero-enteric fistula means a connection between two parts of the intestine. While it might cause a variety of symptoms, air under the diaphragm is not a typical feature.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 801.","responses":[{"text":"Entero-enteric fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bowel perforation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entero-vesicular fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entero-colonic fistula","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20402,"text":"A 25-year-old man is brought to the emergency after being stabbed in the thigh in the middle of a robbery. Which of the following is the most important dimension to measure in case of a stab wound?","explanation":"**Depth** is the most important dimension to measure in a stab wound because it can indicate how far the weapon or object penetrated into the body. This can help in determining the potential for injury to underlying structures such as vessels, organs, and other tissues. In the thigh, for example, important structures like the femoral artery and vein could be injured, and understanding the depth of the wound helps guide medical interventions and determine the necessity for surgical exploration.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile the length of a wound can provide some information about the weapon or object that caused it, it doesn't necessarily indicate the extent of internal damage or potential injury to deeper structures.\r\n\r\nWidth of the stab wound may be more relevant in incised (slash) wounds but is less critical in stab wounds.\r\n\r\nCircumference is not typically used to describe wounds. It is more relevant to describe round or tubular objects.\r\n\r\nLike width, diameter can provide some information but is not as critical as depth in the context of a stab wound.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diameter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Width","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Circumference","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20403,"text":"A 45-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of malodorous, greasy stools along with right upper quadrant pain. A percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography is done, and the X-ray reveals masses in the gallbladder and cystic duct along with the dilation of bile canaliculi. Which of the following will have the highest elevation in serum when liver function test (LFTs) is done?","explanation":"The clinical presentation in this patient suggests a possible **obstructive jaundice** due to the masses in the gallbladder and cystic duct, which could be obstructing the flow of bile. In obstructive jaundice, **alkaline phosphatase (ALP)** typically shows the greatest elevation in comparison to other liver enzymes.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAspartate aminotransferase (AST) and Alanine aminotransferase (ALT) are liver enzymes that get elevated primarily in hepatocellular damage, like in viral hepatitis or drug-induced liver injury. While they can be elevated in obstructive jaundice, their increase is not as significant as ALP.\r\n\r\nIndirect bilirubin would be elevated in conditions that cause increased hemolysis or decreased uptake/conjugation by the liver. In obstructive jaundice, the direct (or conjugated) bilirubin would be elevated due to the backup of bile into the liver and bloodstream.\r\n\r\nPlasma protein levels, including albumin, may decrease in chronic liver diseases due to the liver's decreased synthetic capacity, but they are not the primary markers for cholestasis or bile obstruction.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 397.","responses":[{"text":"Plasma protein levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect bilurbin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspartate aminotransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alanine aminotransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20404,"text":"A 50-year-old female comes to the hospital with complaints of right upper quadrant pain after eating fatty meals. In general appearance, the woman is obese. X-ray shows masses in the gall bladder. The presence of gallstones is confirmed and the woman undergoes laparoscopic cholecystectomy, which reveals jet-black stones that are soft and glassy in appearance. Which of the following is the major composition of the gallstones in this patient?","explanation":"The description of the gallstones as being \"jet-black\" and \"soft and glassy\" in appearance is indicative of **pigment** stones. These types of stones are composed primarily of bilirubin, which is a breakdown product of hemoglobin from old red blood cells.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCalcium phosphate stones are more commonly associated with renal calculi rather than gallstones.\r\n\r\nCalcium oxalate stones, like calcium phosphate, are also more typical of kidney stones rather than gallstones.\r\n\r\nMixed stones in the gallbladder have components of both cholesterol and pigment but may not be specifically described as jet-black and soft.\r\n\r\nCholesterol stones are the most common type of gallstones and are often described as yellow-green in color. They are formed when the liver excretes more cholesterol in the bile than can be dissolved. They are not typically described as jet-black and soft.\r\n\r\nIn the case of the patient described, her presentation aligns most closely with pigment stones.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 874.","responses":[{"text":"Mixed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pigment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium oxalate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20405,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with complaints of abdominal pain and yellowing of the sclera. Which of the following is the best first-line investigation to do in this patient?","explanation":"For a patient presenting with **abdominal pain and jaundice (yellowing of the sclera)**, the best first-line investigation to evaluate the hepatobiliary system and determine the cause of his symptoms is **ultrasound**. It is non-invasive, widely available, cost-effective, and can quickly identify gallstones, tumors, or other obstructions in the bile ducts and liver.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nX-ray of the abdomen can be useful for identifying gas patterns and may detect some types of stones, but it is not the best choice for evaluating the liver and bile ducts.\r\n\r\nBarium swallow is primarily used to evaluate the esophagus and, to some extent, the stomach. It is not appropriate for a primary investigation of jaundice.\r\n\r\nMagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) provides detailed images of the hepatobiliary system and pancreatic ducts without the need for invasive procedures or ionizing radiation. It is useful if there is a suspicion of choledocholithiasis (stones in the common bile duct) or other ductal abnormalities, but it is not typically a first-line investigation due to its cost and availability.\r\n\r\nComputerized tomography (CT) can provide detailed cross-sectional images of the abdomen, including the liver and bile ducts. It might be used in more complex cases or when other tests are inconclusive, but ultrasound is typically preferred as the initial imaging study because it's quicker, cheaper, and doesn't involve radiation.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 854.","responses":[{"text":"Computerized tomography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium swallow","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20436,"text":"A 20-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with right upper quadrant pain and pruritis along with severe diarrhea for the past 1 month. A percutaneous transhepatic cholangiogram is performed on the patient, which reveals a beaded appearance of the extrahepatic bile ducts. Which of the following is the most likely cause of diarrhea in this patient?","explanation":"The **beaded appearance of the extrahepatic bile ducts** on a percutaneous transhepatic cholangiogram in a patient with right upper quadrant pain, pruritis, and diarrhea is suggestive of **primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC)**. PSC is a chronic liver disease characterized by inflammation and scarring of the bile ducts, leading to their narrowing and strictures.\r\n\r\nThe most likely cause of diarrhea in this patient is **ulcerative colitis**. Ulcerative colitis is a form of inflammatory bowel disease. PSC and ulcerative colitis have a known association. Many patients with PSC also have ulcerative colitis, and the presence of one condition increases the risk of developing the other.\r\n\r\nCrohn's disease is another form of inflammatory bowel disease, but it is not as strongly associated with PSC.\r\n\r\nCholelithiasis refers to the presence of gallstones, and while it can cause right upper quadrant pain, it does not typically result in the beaded appearance on imaging or cause persistent diarrhea. \r\n\r\nClonorchis infection, caused by the *Clonorchis sinensis* liver fluke, can lead to biliary tract issues, but it doesn't produce the classic beaded appearance associated with PSC. \r\n\r\nGastroenteritis can cause diarrhea, but it does not lead to the characteristic imaging findings of PSC.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 135, 136.","responses":[{"text":"Clonorchis infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroenteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20437,"text":"Apart from ammonia, which of the following substances also accumulate in the blood in case of acute liver failure?","explanation":"In the case of acute liver failure, apart from ammonia, **bilirubin** also accumulates in the blood.\r\n\r\nThe liver plays a vital role in the metabolism and excretion of bilirubin. When the liver is damaged, as in **acute liver failure**, it cannot process or excrete bilirubin effectively, leading to its accumulation in the blood. This results in **jaundice**, where the skin and the whites of the eyes become yellow. Elevated bilirubin levels can indicate liver dysfunction.\r\n\r\nCholesterol is synthesized in the liver, and liver damage can affect cholesterol levels, but it does not typically accumulate in acute liver failure. \r\n\r\nTyrosine is an amino acid and its metabolism can be affected in liver disorders, but it is not a primary concern in acute liver failure. \r\n\r\nGlycogen is stored in the liver, and liver failure can affect glucose metabolism, but again, it does not accumulate in the blood in acute liver failure. \r\n\r\nBile salts are produced in the liver and help in the digestion of fats; their levels can be affected in liver diseases, but bilirubin is the primary substance of concern that accumulates in the blood in acute liver failure.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 860, 861.","responses":[{"text":"Glycogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bile salts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biluribin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20438,"text":"Which of the following is the investigation of choice in a person who developed colonic strictures after a large bowel resection is done due to a colorectal carcinoma?","explanation":"Given the history of **colorectal carcinoma** and **subsequent surgery**, there is a need to directly visualize the stricture and obtain tissue samples to determine if there is a **recurrence of the cancer**, making **colonoscopy with biopsy** the most suitable choice.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBarium enema is a radiological examination of the large intestine. It can show strictures, tumors, and other abnormalities but doesn't allow for a direct view or biopsy.\r\n\r\nSpiral computerized tomography (CT) is a type of CT scan that provides images quicker than traditional CT scans. It's valuable for many conditions, but when there is a suspicion of recurrent cancer or complications post-surgery in the colon, direct visualization and biopsy via colonoscopy would be preferred.\r\n\r\nComputerized tomography with contrast provides detailed images of the abdomen and can highlight areas of concern, but it does not allow for a direct visualization or biopsy of the stricture.\r\n\r\nAn ultrasound provides real-time images of the organs in the abdomen. It can detect masses and other abnormalities but lacks the resolution and specificity of a CT scan or the direct visualization and biopsy capability of a colonoscopy.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 832.","responses":[{"text":"Computerized tomography with contrast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium enema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colonoscopy with biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spiral computerized tomography","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20439,"text":"A 30-year-old male is brought in an unconscious state to the emergency department after a road traffic accident. After regaining consciousness, the patient realizes that he can neither feel nor move his lower limbs. On examination, the gut sounds are absent, and the doctor suspects paralytic ileus. Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient's condition?","explanation":"The patient's presentation of being unable to feel or move his lower limbs after a road traffic accident, coupled with the clinical signs of absent gut sounds, points towards a neurological cause of **paralytic ileus**. In this context, the most likely cause of the patient's condition is **spinal cord injury**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nHypokalemia can cause muscle weakness, cramps, and in severe cases, paralysis. However, it would not be the primary suspect in a patient who has just been in a road traffic accident and presents with acute paralysis.\r\n\r\nMesenteric ischemia is a condition where there's reduced blood flow to the intestines due to blockage of the mesenteric arteries. It presents with severe abdominal pain, especially post meals, and not primarily with paralysis.\r\n\r\nColorectal carcinoma would present with signs and symptoms related to the bowel, like change in bowel habits, rectal bleeding, or unexplained weight loss, and not acute paralysis following trauma.\r\n\r\nElevated sodium levels can lead to altered mental status, muscle twitching, and seizures. It does not present with acute paralysis of the lower limbs, especially in the context of a recent traumatic event.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 161.","responses":[{"text":"Colorectal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesenteric ischemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cord injury","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20440,"text":"A 63-year-old male, who is a heavy smoker, complains of food sticking behind his sternum for the last 5 months. He has lost considerable weight and appears malnourished. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy and biopsy confirm the malignant growth. What should be assessed first before commencing the therapy?","explanation":"In a patient with suspected adenocarcinoma of the esophagus, establishing a definitive diagnosis and determining the extent of the disease (staging) is critical before initiating any treatment. \r\n\r\nThe most appropriate investigation before starting treatment for a confirmed case of adenocarcinoma of the esophagus is **CT abdomen and thorax**. This will help in staging the tumor, determining the presence of any metastatic disease, and guiding the therapeutic approach.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nA biopsy is essential to confirm the diagnosis. Tissue is typically obtained during an endoscopic procedure and is then examined under a microscope to determine if cancer cells are present.\r\n\r\nEndoscopy is an essential diagnostic tool for visualizing the tumor and obtaining tissue for biopsy. In esophageal cancer, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) can also be done, which helps determine the depth of tumor invasion and assess for nearby lymph node involvement.\r\n\r\nBarium swallow is a radiographic examination of the esophagus. A patient swallows barium contrast, which outlines the esophagus on X-ray. This can help visualize the location and size of the tumor, but it's less frequently used now because endoscopy and CT scans provide more detailed information.\r\n\r\nUltrasound is not typically the first-line investigation for esophageal cancer. However, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is a specialized form of ultrasound used in esophageal cancer to determine how deeply the tumor has invaded the esophageal wall and whether nearby lymph nodes are affected.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 796.","responses":[{"text":"CT scan of abdomen and chest","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Multimodal therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General health and nutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritoneal spread","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distant metastasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20441,"text":"What is the appropriate treatment strategy for a patient with a positive HBsAg, positive HbE, a hepatitis B viral load of 40,000 /dl, coexisting hepatitis C genotype 1, and a fibro scan result indicating the F2 fibrosis stage?","explanation":"In a patient with coexisting hepatitis B (HBV) and hepatitis C (HCV) infections, the management can be challenging.\r\n\r\n1. **HBsAg positive and positive HbE with a viral load of 40,000/dl**: These markers indicate that the patient has active HBV replication. The viral load, though not extremely high, is significant enough to consider treatment.\r\n\r\n2. **Coexisting hepatitis C genotype 1**: HCV genotype 1 used to be one of the more difficult genotypes to treat, but with the introduction of direct-acting antiviral (DAA) agents, the treatment outcomes have significantly improved.\r\n\r\n3. **F2 fibrosis on FibroScan**: This indicates moderate liver fibrosis. FibroScan is a type of elastography that measures liver stiffness, which correlates with the degree of liver fibrosis. F2 fibrosis suggests there's significant scarring, but it's not yet cirrhosis.\r\n  \r\n**Pegylated interferon alpha** has been used both for HBV and HCV. It's administered as a weekly injection and can have significant side effects. For HCV genotype 1, pegylated interferon used to be combined with ribavirin, but this approach has been largely replaced by oral DAA regimens which are more effective and better tolerated. Additionally, interferon therapy for 24 weeks might not be sufficient for HCV genotype 1, as traditionally, 48 weeks were recommended for this genotype.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Lamivudine** and **adefovir** are antiviral agents used to treat hepatitis B. However, resistance can develop with Lamivudine, especially when used for extended periods. Adefovir is also an option, but there are now more potent and safer drugs available.\r\n  \r\n**Entecavir** is a potent antiviral agent against HBV and has a lower resistance profile compared to lamivudine. However, a treatment duration of just 1 month is not standard; usually, treatment is longer term.\r\nght be more appropriate. The patient should be managed by a hepatologist or infectious disease specialist familiar with the treatment of viral hepatitis co-infections.","reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 438.\r\n\r\n(2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 876.","responses":[{"text":"Pegylated interferon alpha for 24 weeks","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entecavir for 1 month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine for 3 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir for 3 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No treatment required as viral load is low","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

